gh School|Manchester Essex Regional High School]]\n* [[Marblehead High School]]\n* [[Masconomet Regional High School]], serves [[Topsfield, Massachusetts|Topsfield]], [[Boxford, Massachusetts|Boxford]] and [[Middleton, Massachusetts|Middleton]]\n* [[Methuen High School]]\n* [[Newburyport High School]]\n* [[North Andover High School]]\n* [[Northshore Academy, Beverly|Northshore Academy]]\n* [[Peabody Veterans Memorial High School]]\n* [[Pentucket Regional High School]], serves [[Groveland, Massachusetts|Groveland]], [[Merrimac, Massachusetts|Merrimac]] and [[West Newbury, Massachusetts|West Newbury]]\n* [[Rockport High School]]\n* [[Salem High School (Massachusetts)|Salem High School]]\n* [[Saugus High School (Massachusetts)|Saugus High School]]\n* Swampscott High School,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120915015754/http://highschool.swampscott.k12.ma.us/pages/index Swampscott High School]</ref> serves [[Swampscott, Massachusetts|Swampscott]] and [[Nahant, Massachusetts|Nahant]]\n* [[Triton Regional High School (Massachusetts)|Triton Regional High School]], serves [[Newbury, Massachusetts|Newbury]], [[Rowley, Massachusetts|Rowley]] and [[Salisbury, Massachusetts|Salisbury]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n====Technical schools====\n{{Columns-list|\n* [[Essex Agricultural and Technical High School]]\n* [[Greater Lawrence Technical School]]\n* [[Lynn Vocational and Technical Institute]]\n* [[North Shore Technical High School]]\n* [[Whittier Regional Vocational Technical High School]]\n}}\n\n====Private schools====\n{{Columns-list|\n* [[Academy at Penguin Hall]]\n* [[Bishop Fenwick High School (Peabody, Massachusetts)|Bishop Fenwick High School]]\n* [[Bradford Christian Academy (Haverhill, Massachusetts)|Bradford Christian Academy]]\n* [[Brooks School]]\n* [[Central Catholic High School (Lawrence, Massachusetts)|Central Catholic High School]]\n* [[The Clark School (Rowley, Massachusetts)]]\n* [[The Governor's Academy]]\n* [[Phillips Academy]]\n* [[Pingree School]]\n* [[Presentation of Mary Academy]]\n* [[St. John's Preparatory School (Danvers, Massachusetts)|St. John's Preparatory School]]\n* [[St. Mary's High School (Lynn, Massachusetts)|St. Mary's High School]]\n* [[The Waring School]]\n}}\n\n===Higher education===\n{{Columns-list|\n* [[Endicott College]]\n* [[Gordon College (Massachusetts)|Gordon College]]\n* [[Gordon-Conwell Theological Seminary]]\n* [[Marian Court College]] - Now closed\n* [[Massachusetts School of Law]]\n* [[Merrimack College]]\n* [[Montserrat College of Art]]\n* [[North Shore Community College]]\n* [[Northern Essex Community College]]\n* [[Northpoint Bible College]]\n* [[Salem State University]]\n}}\n\n==Economy==\n===Employment===\nAs of 2015, the county had total employment of 282,412.<ref name=quickfacts/> The largest employer in the county is [[Massachusetts General Hospital]], with over 5,000 employees.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://lmi2.detma.org/lmi/Top_employer_list.asp?gstfips=25&areatype=04&gCountyCode=000009 | title=Largest 200 Employers in Essex County | publisher=[[Massachusetts Executive Office of Labor and Workforce Development]]}}</ref>\n\n===Banking===\nBased on deposits in the county, the five largest banks are [[TD Bank, N.A.]], [[Salem Five Cents Bank]], [[Institution for Savings]], [[Bank of America]], and [[Eastern Bank]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www5.fdic.gov/sod/sodMarketRpt.asp?barItem=2 | title=Deposit Market Share Report | publisher=[[Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation]]}}</ref>\n\n==Essex National Heritage Area==\n{{see also|List of Registered Historic Places in Essex County, Massachusetts}}\nOn November 12, 1996, Essex [[U.S. National Heritage Area|National Heritage Area]] (ENHA) was authorized by Congress. The heritage area consists of all of Essex County, MA a {{convert|500|sqmi|km2|adj=on}} area between the Atlantic Coast and the Merrimack Valley. The area includes 34 cities and towns; two National Historic Sites (Salem Maritime National Historic Site and Saugus Iron Works National Historic Site); and thousands of historic sites and districts that illuminate colonial settlement, the development of the shoe and textile industries, and the growth and decline of the maritime industries, including fishing, privateering, and the China trade.<ref>''The National Parks: Index 2001-2003,'' Washington, D.C.: [[National Park Service]], p. 104.</ref> The Essex National Heritage Area<ref>[http://www.essexheritage.org/ Essex National Heritage Area]</ref> is one of 49 heritage areas designated by Congress, affiliated with the National Park Service.\n\nThe [[Essex National Heritage Commission]] is a non-profit organization chartered to promote tourism and cultural awareness of the area, connecting people to the places of Essex County, MA. The Commission's mission is to promote and preserve the historic, cultural and natural resources of the ENHA by rallying community support around saving the character of the area. This is accomplished through the commission's projects and programs, which include Partnership Grant Program, Explorers membership program, photo safaris, and the annual September weekend event Trails & Sails,<ref>[http://www.essexheritage.org/ts/ Trails & Sails]</ref> as well as other important regional partnership building projects like the [[Essex Heritage]] Scenic Byway, and the Border to Boston trail.\n\n==Communities==\nThe towns and cities of Essex County are listed below.\n\n===Cities===\n{{Div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Amesbury, Massachusetts|Amesbury]]\n* [[Beverly, Massachusetts|Beverly]]\n* [[Gloucester, Massachusetts|Gloucester]]\n* [[Haverhill, Massachusetts|Haverhill]]\n* [[Lawrence, Massachusetts|Lawrence]] (traditional county seat)\n* [[Lynn, Massachusetts|Lynn]]\n* [[Methuen, Massachusetts|Methuen]]\n* [[Newburyport, Massachusetts|Newburyport]]\n* [[Peabody, Massachusetts|Peabody]]\n* [[Salem, Massachusetts|Salem]] (traditional county seat)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Towns===\n{{Div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover]]\n* [[Boxford, Massachusetts|Boxford]]\n* [[Danvers, Massachusetts|Danvers]] (Salem Village)\n* [[Essex, Massachusetts|Essex]]\n* [[Georgetown, Massachusetts|Georgetown]]\n* [[Groveland, Massachusetts|Groveland]]\n* [[Hamilton, Massachusetts|Hamilton]]\n* [[Ipswich, Massachusetts|Ipswich]]\n* [[Lynnfield, Massachusetts|Lynnfield]]\n* [[Manchester-by-the-Sea, Massachusetts|Manchester-by-the-Sea]]\n* [[Marblehead, Massachusetts|Marblehead]]\n* [[Merrimac, Massachusetts|Merrimac]]\n* [[Middleton, Massachusetts|Middleton]]\n* [[Nahant, Massachusetts|Nahant]]\n* [[Newbury, Massachusetts|Newbury]]\n* [[North Andover, Massachusetts|North Andover]]\n* [[Rockport, Massachusetts|Rockport]]\n* [[Rowley, Massachusetts|Rowley]]\n* [[Salisbury, Massachusetts|Salisbury]]\n* [[Saugus, Massachusetts|Saugus]]\n* [[Swampscott, Massachusetts|Swampscott]]\n* [[Topsfield, Massachusetts|Topsfield]]\n* [[Wenham, Massachusetts|Wenham]]\n* [[West Newbury, Massachusetts|West Newbury]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Census-designated places===\n{{Div col}}\n*[[Andover (CDP), Massachusetts|Andover]]\n*[[Boxford (CDP), Massachusetts|Boxford]]\n*[[Essex (CDP), Massachusetts|Essex]]\n*[[Ipswich (CDP), Massachusetts|Ipswich]]\n*[[Rockport (CDP), Massachusetts|Rockport]]\n*[[Rowley (CDP), Massachusetts|Rowley]]\n*[[Salisbury (CDP), Massachusetts|Salisbury]]\n*[[Topsfield (CDP), Massachusetts|Topsfield]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Other villages===\n{{Div col}}\n*[[Annisquam, Massachusetts|Annisquam]]\n*[[Ballardvale, Massachusetts|Ballardvale]]\n*[[Beverly Farms]]\n*[[Bradford, Massachusetts|Bradford]]\n*[[Byfield, Massachusetts|Byfield]]\n*[[Clifton, Massachusetts|Clifton]]\n*[[Magnolia, Massachusetts|Magnolia]]\n*[[Merrimacport, Massachusetts|Merrimacport]]\n*[[Rocks Village, Massachusetts|Rocks Village]]\n*[[Plum Island, Massachusetts|Plum Island]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n* [[Essex Junto]]\n* [[Tinker's Island]]\n* [[Lovecraft Country]]\n* [[Registry of Deeds (Massachusetts)#Essex|Registry of Deeds (Massachusetts)]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Essex County, Massachusetts]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{ cite book | ref=harv | editor-last=Arrington | editor-first=Benjamin F. | title=Municipal History of Essex County in Massachusetts | volume=Volume I | edition=Tercentenary | year=1922A | location=New York | publisher=Lewis Historical Publishing Company | url=https://books.google.com/?id=1HAMAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Amesbury+Massachusetts+incorporation#v=onepage}}\n* {{ cite book | ref=harv | editor-last=Arrington | editor-first=Benjamin F. | title=Municipal History of Essex County in Massachusetts | volume=Volume II | edition=Tercentenary | year=1922B | location=New York | publisher=Lewis Historical Publishing Company | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C3EMAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Municipal+History+of+Essex+County+in+Massachusetts}}\n* {{ cite book | ref=harv | editor-last=Arrington | editor-first=Benjamin F. | title=Municipal History of Essex County in Massachusetts | volume=Volume III | edition=Tercentenary | year=1922C | location=New York | publisher=Lewis Historical Publishing Company | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RHEMAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Municipal+History+of+Essex+County+in+Massachusetts}}\n* {{ cite book | ref=harv | editor-last=Arrington | editor-first=Benjamin F. | title=Municipal History of Essex County in Massachusetts | volume=Volume IV | edition=Tercentenary | year=1922D | location=New York | publisher=Lewis Historical Publishing Company | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g3EMAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Municipal+History+of+Essex+County+in+Massachusetts}}\n*Hurd, Duane Hamilton. History of Essex County, Massachusetts: With Biographical Sketches of Many Pioneers and Prominent Men. [https://books.google.com/books?id=4da_fyBBU1IC&printsec=title&dq=History+of+Essex+County Volume 1]. [https://books.google.com/books?id=YUoWAAAAY