{"title_page": "Renkus-Heinz", "text_new": "{{Infobox company |\n  name =  Renkus-Heinz|\n  logo =  RH-logo.png |\n  image = \n[[File:Renkus-Heinz Headquarters Building Exterior.jpg|thumb|The Renkus-Heinz headquarters in Foothill Ranch, California]]\n |\n  type =   |\n  foundation =   1979 |\n  founders = Harro K. Heinz, Algis Renkus|\n  location =  [[Foothill Ranch, California]], United States |\n  key_people =  Matt Czyzewski, President Harro K. Heinz, CEO|\n  industry =  [[Audio electronics]] |\n  products =  [[Loudspeaker]]s |\n  num_employees  =  |\n  homepage = http://www.renkus-heinz.com\n}}\n\n'''Renkus-Heinz''' is a California-based manufacturer of [[loudspeaker]]s and related professional sound reinforcement equipment specializing in steerable audio technology. Based in [[Foothill Ranch, California]],<ref name=\"audioannuals\"/> the firm has a global presence in permanent installations at [[auditorium]]s, transit centers,<ref>[http://www.renkus-heinz.com/applications/venues/auditoriums/auditoriums.html Renkus-Heinz. Auditorium / Transit]</ref> sports venues,<ref>[http://www.renkus-heinz.com/applications/venues/sport/sport.html Renkus-Heinz. Sports]</ref> [[Place of worship|houses of worship]]<ref>[http://www.rh.com/applications/venues/worship/worship.html Renkus-Heinz. Houses of Worship]</ref> and [[Music venue|musical performance venues]]<ref>[http://www.rh.com/applications/venues/PA-theatres/pa-theatres.html Renkus-Heinz. Performing Arts / Theatres]</ref> as well as in the [[Concert#Concert tour|concert touring industry]].<ref>[http://www.rh.com/applications/venues/rental/tour-rental.html Renkus-Heinz. Tour / Rental]</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Design and Architecture Norway's Machine Hall Building.jpg|thumb|Design and Architecture Norway's Machine Hall Building]]\n[[File:Harro Heinz.jpg|thumb|Renkus-Heinz Founder and CEO Harro Heinz]]\n[[File:Matt Czyzewski Renkus-Heinz headshot.jpg|thumb|Renkus-Heinz President Matt Czyzewski]]\n\nRenkus-Heinz was founded on April 1, 1979 by Harro K. Heinz and Algis Renkus (1937\u20131997<ref>[http://www.arx.com.au/International/Algis.htm ARX.com. ''Algis Renkus memoriam'']</ref>).<ref name=\"audioannuals\">{{cite web |url=http://www.audioannals.com/co-p-s.htm |title=Companies P-Q-R-S Renkus-Heinz |publisher=Audioannals.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040903152225/http://www.audioannals.com/co-p-s.htm |archive-date=September 3, 2004 |accessdate=April 16, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Heinz had previously been awarded a patent in 1975 for his work on a \"Comprehensive feedback elimination system employing notch filter\"<ref>{{US patent reference\n | number = 4088835\n | y = 1975\n | m = 05\n | d = 09\n | inventor = Harro K. Heinz\n | title = Comprehensive feedback elimination system employing notch filter\n}}</ref> that was performed while he was employed at [[Rauland Borg]] Corporation, the company he left to found Renkus-Heinz.<ref>[http://www.audioannals.com/bio-g-h.htm#HeinzH Audioannals.com. Biography G\u2013H. ''Harro Heinz'']</ref> Algis Renkus was joined in the new enterprise by his father Jonas A. Renkus (b. 1912) who had worked at [[Altec Lansing|Altec]] under industry veteran [[John Kenneth Hilliard]].\n\nWhile at Renkus Heinz, Jonas Renkus patented a new triple lamination construction method in 1980. In 1981, the two Renkus men left Renkus-Heinz to assist Emilar, which was having trouble staying in business. Harro Heinz remained president of Renkus-Heinz.\n\nWhile Jonas and Algis Renkus were at Emilar, they began using the patented triple lamination method which had been assigned to Renkus-Heinz. Heinz sued for damages but dropped the case during the hearing.<ref>[http://www.audioheritage.org/vbulletin/showthread.php?t=13717 Audioheritage.org. Robert Grunberg bulletin board entry ''Jonas Renkus and his Bowtie horn'' posted December 28, 2006.]</ref>\n\nIn 1989 Harro's son Ralph D. Heinz joined Renkus-Heinz to work with Don B. Keele, Jr. and Gene Patronis and further his knowledge of electro-acoustics and [[horn loudspeaker]] design. Ralph Heinz eventually became senior vice-president of [[Research and development|R&D]]<ref>[http://www.aes.org/sections/la/archive/2000/2000-10.pdf AES Los Angeles section. October 2000. ''A Field Trip to Renkus-Heinz'']</ref> and patented a method of arraying loudspeakers for better phase coherency in 1994.<ref>{{US patent|5750943}}</ref> In 1996, he patented a [[Loudspeaker enclosure#Multiple entry horn|multiple driver horn]] which was promoted as the \"CoEntrant\" transducer, covering both mid- and high-frequency bands in one horn.<ref>[http://svconline.com/mag/avinstall_renkusheinz_coentrant_transducer/ Sound & Video Contractor. April 1, 1999. Ralph Heinz. ''The Renkus-Heinz CoEntrant transducer'']</ref> In 2016, Ralph Heinz was named Chief Technical Officer.<ref>{{cite news |last1=SCN Staff |title=Renkus-Heinz Announces Reorganization of Leadership |url=https://www.avnetwork.com/avnetwork/renkus-heinz-announces-reorganization-of-leadership |publisher=AVNetwork |date=May 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Harro\u2019s daughter Monika Heinz Smetona joined Renkus-Heinz as on the administrative team and was named chief operating officer in 2016. She was then named chief financial officer in 2019.\u201d \n\nIn May 2019, Matt Czyzewski joined Renkus-Heinz as president, following a 22-year tenure at Biamp.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mullen |first1=Amanda |title=Matt Czyzewski Appointed President Of Renkus-Heinz |url=https://www.soundandcommunications.com/matt-czyzewski-appointed-president-of-renkus-heinz/ |publisher=Sound & Communications Media |date=April 2, 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Patents==\n*{{US patent reference\n | number = 4336425\n | y = 1980\n | m = 05\n | d = 06\n | inventor = Jonas A. Renkus\n | title = HIGH FREQUENCY COMPRESSION DRIVER AND METHOD OF MANUFACTURE THEREOF\n}}\n*{{US patent reference\n | number = 4887298\n | y = 1988\n | m = 06\n | d = 15\n | inventor = Robert M. Haigler\n | title = ELECTRONIC CIRCUIT FOR SENSING DISCONNECT OR FAILURE OF A POWER OUTPUT SENSE LINE IN AN AUDIO POWER SYSTEM\n}}\n*{{US patent reference\n | number = 5750943\n | y = 1994\n | m = 02\n | d = 15\n | inventor = Ralph D. Heinz\n | title = SPEAKER ARRAY WITH IMPROVED PHASE CHARACTERISTICS\n}}\n*{{US patent reference\n | number = 5526456\n | y = 1996\n | m = 06\n | d = 11\n | inventor = Ralph D. Heinz\n | title = Multiple-driver single horn loud speaker\n}}\n\n==Products==\n*ICLive X Series\n*Directivity Control Series\n*ICONYX Gen5\n*VARIA-RN & RD\n\n==Awards==\n*LSI\u2019s Readers\u2019 Choice Award for the ICLive X series\n*Best Audio Products: Large-Format Loudspeaker\n*Rental & Staging Systems Best of Show Award for the ICLive X series<ref>{{cite news |last1=SVC Staff |title=Rental & Staging Systems announces Best of Show InfoComm 2019 Awards |url=https://www.svconline.com/svc-event/rental-staging-systems-announces-best-of-show-infocomm-2019-awards |publisher=Future Media |date=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n*rAVe [Pubs] The Best of ISE 2019 Award for the DC12/2<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kayye |first1=Gary |title=Here Are the Best of ISE 2019 Awards \u2013 AV\u2019s Only NOT-Pay-for-Play Awards |url=https://www.ravepubs.com/best-of-ise-2019-awards/ |publisher=THE rAVe Agency |date=March 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Meyer Sound Laboratories]]\n*[[QSC Audio]]\n*[[JBL (company)|JBL]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{externalvideo\n| align = left\n| width = 320px\n| video1 = [https://www.namm.org/library/oral-history/harro-heinz ''Oral History, Harro Heinz recalls the radio business right after the war.'' Interview date September 9, 2011, NAMM (National Association of Music Merchants) Oral History Library]\n|\n}}\n\n[[Category:Audio amplifier manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Manufacturers of professional audio equipment]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies established in 1979]]\n[[Category:Audio equipment manufacturers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Loudspeaker manufacturers]]\n[[Category:1979 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company |\n  name =  Renkus-Heinz|\n  logo =  RH-logo.png |\n  image = \n[[File:Renkus-Heinz Headquarters Building Exterior.jpg|thumb|The Renkus-Heinz headquarters in Foothill Ranch, California]]\n |\n  type =   |\n  foundation =   1979 |\n  founders = Harro K. Heinz, Algis Renkus|\n  location =  [[Foothill Ranch, California]], United States |\n  key_people =  Matt Czyzewski, President Harro K. Heinz, CEO|\n  industry =  [[Audio electronics]] |\n  products =  [[Loudspeaker]]s |\n  num_employees  =  |\n  homepage = http://www.renkus-heinz.com\n}}\n\n'''Renkus-Heinz''' is a California-based manufacturer of [[loudspeaker]]s and related professional sound reinforcement equipment specializing in steerable audio technology. Based in [[Foothill Ranch, California]],<ref name=\"audioannuals\"/> the firm has a global presence in permanent installations at [[auditorium]]s, transit centers,<ref>[http://www.renkus-heinz.com/applications/venues/auditoriums/auditoriums.html Renkus-Heinz. Auditorium / Transit]</ref> sports venues,<ref>[http://www.renkus-heinz.com/applications/venues/sport/sport.html Renkus-Heinz. Sports]</ref> [[Place of worship|houses of worship]]<ref>[http://www.rh.com/applications/venues/worship/worship.html Renkus-Heinz. Houses of Worship]</ref> and [[Music venue|musical performance venues]]<ref>[http://www.rh.com/applications/venues/PA-theatres/pa-theatres.html Renkus-Heinz. Performing Arts / Theatres]</ref> as well as in the [[Concert#Concert tour|concert touring industry]].<ref>[http://www.rh.com/applications/venues/rental/tour-rental.html Renkus-Heinz. Tour / Rental]</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Design and Architecture Norway's Machine Hall Building.jpg|thumb|Design and Architecture Norway's Machine Hall Building]]\n[[File:Harro Heinz.jpg|thumb|Renkus-Heinz Founder and CEO Harro Heinz]]\n[[File:Matt Czyzewski Renkus-Heinz headshot.jpg|thumb|Renkus-Heinz President Matt Czyzewski]]\n\nRenkus-Heinz was founded on April 1, 1979 by Harro K. Heinz and Algis Renkus (1937\u20131997<ref>[http://www.arx.com.au/International/Algis.htm ARX.com. ''Algis Renkus memoriam'']</ref>).<ref name=\"audioannuals\">{{cite web |url=http://www.audioannals.com/co-p-s.htm |title=Companies P-Q-R-S Renkus-Heinz |publisher=Audioannals.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040903152225/http://www.audioannals.com/co-p-s.htm |archive-date=September 3, 2004 |accessdate=April 16, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Heinz had previously been awarded a patent in 1975 for his work on a \"Comprehensive feedback elimination system employing notch filter\"<ref>{{US patent reference\n | number = 4088835\n | y = 1975\n | m = 05\n | d = 09\n | inventor = Harro K. Heinz\n | title = Comprehensive feedback elimination system employing notch filter\n}}</ref> that was performed while he was employed at [[Rauland Borg]] Corporation, the company he left to found Renkus-Heinz.<ref>[http://www.audioannals.com/bio-g-h.htm#HeinzH Audioannals.com. Biography G\u2013H. ''Harro Heinz'']</ref> Algis Renkus was joined in the new enterprise by his father Jonas A. Renkus (b. 1912) who had worked at [[Altec Lansing|Altec]] under industry veteran [[John Kenneth Hilliard]].\n\nWhile at Renkus Heinz, Jonas Renkus patented a new triple lamination construction method in 1980. In 1981, the two Renkus men left Renkus-Heinz to assist Emilar, which was having trouble staying in business. Harro Heinz remained president of Renkus-Heinz.\n\nWhile Jonas and Algis Renkus were at Emilar, they began using the patented triple lamination method which had been assigned to Renkus-Heinz. Heinz sued for damages but dropped the case during the hearing.<ref>[http://www.audioheritage.org/vbulletin/showthread.php?t=13717 Audioheritage.org. Robert Grunberg bulletin board entry ''Jonas Renkus and his Bowtie horn'' posted December 28, 2006.]</ref>\n\nIn 1989 Harro's son Ralph D. Heinz joined Renkus-Heinz to work with Don B. Keele, Jr. and Gene Patronis and further his knowledge of electro-acoustics and [[horn loudspeaker]] design. Ralph Heinz eventually became senior vice-president of [[Research and development|R&D]]<ref>[http://www.aes.org/sections/la/archive/2000/2000-10.pdf AES Los Angeles section. October 2000. ''A Field Trip to Renkus-Heinz'']</ref> and patented a method of arraying loudspeakers for better phase coherency in 1994.<ref>{{US patent|5750943}}</ref> In 1996, he patented a [[Loudspeaker enclosure#Multiple entry horn|multiple driver horn]] which was promoted as the \"CoEntrant\" transducer, covering both mid- and high-frequency bands in one horn.<ref>[http://svconline.com/mag/avinstall_renkusheinz_coentrant_transducer/ Sound & Video Contractor. April 1, 1999. Ralph Heinz. ''The Renkus-Heinz CoEntrant transducer'']</ref> In 2016, Ralph Heinz was named Chief Technical Officer.<ref>{{cite news |last1=SCN Staff |title=Renkus-Heinz Announces Reorganization of Leadership |url=https://www.avnetwork.com/avnetwork/renkus-heinz-announces-reorganization-of-leadership |publisher=AVNetwork |date=May 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Harro\u2019s daughter Monika Heinz Smetona joined Renkus-Heinz as on the administrative team and was named chief operating officer in 2016. She was then named chief financial officer in 2019.\u201d \n\nIn May 2019, Matt Czyzewski joined Renkus-Heinz as president, following a 22-year tenure at Biamp.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mullen |first1=Amanda |title=Matt Czyzewski Appointed President Of Renkus-Heinz |url=https://www.soundandcommunications.com/matt-czyzewski-appointed-president-of-renkus-heinz/ |publisher=Sound & Communications Media |date=April 2, 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Patents==\n*{{US patent reference\n | number = 4336425\n | y = 1980\n | m = 05\n | d = 06\n | inventor = Jonas A. Renkus\n | title = HIGH FREQUENCY COMPRESSION DRIVER AND METHOD OF MANUFACTURE THEREOF\n}}\n*{{US patent reference\n | number = 4887298\n | y = 1988\n | m = 06\n | d = 15\n | inventor = Robert M. Haigler\n | title = ELECTRONIC CIRCUIT FOR SENSING DISCONNECT OR FAILURE OF A POWER OUTPUT SENSE LINE IN AN AUDIO POWER SYSTEM\n}}\n*{{US patent reference\n | number = 5750943\n | y = 1994\n | m = 02\n | d = 15\n | inventor = Ralph D. Heinz\n | title = SPEAKER ARRAY WITH IMPROVED PHASE CHARACTERISTICS\n}}\n*{{US patent reference\n | number = 5526456\n | y = 1996\n | m = 06\n | d = 11\n | inventor = Ralph D. Heinz\n | title = Multiple-driver single horn loud speaker\n}}\n\n==Products==\n*ICLive X Series\n*Directivity Control Series\n*ICONYX Gen5\n*VARIA-RN & RD\n\n\n==Awards==\n*LSI\u2019s Readers\u2019 Choice Award for the ICLive X series\n*Best Audio Products: Large-Format Loudspeaker\n*Rental & Staging Systems Best of Show Award for the ICLive X series<ref>{{cite news |last1=SVC Staff |title=Rental & Staging Systems announces Best of Show InfoComm 2019 Awards |url=https://www.svconline.com/svc-event/rental-staging-systems-announces-best-of-show-infocomm-2019-awards |publisher=Future Media |date=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n*rAVe [Pubs] The Best of ISE 2019 Award for the DC12/2<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kayye |first1=Gary |title=Here Are the Best of ISE 2019 Awards \u2013 AV\u2019s Only NOT-Pay-for-Play Awards |url=https://www.ravepubs.com/best-of-ise-2019-awards/ |publisher=THE rAVe Agency |date=March 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Meyer Sound Laboratories]]\n*[[QSC Audio]]\n*[[JBL (company)|JBL]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{externalvideo\n| align = left\n| width = 320px\n| video1 = [https://www.namm.org/library/oral-history/harro-heinz ''Oral History, Harro Heinz recalls the radio business right after the war.'' Interview date September 9, 2011, NAMM (National Association of Music Merchants) Oral History Library]\n|\n}}\n\n[[Category:Audio amplifier manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Manufacturers of professional audio equipment]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies established in 1