{"title_page": "Tulip Siddiq", "text_new": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Tulip Siddiq\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n\n|honorific-prefix =\n\n| image            = Official portrait of Tulip Siddiq crop 2.jpg\n| caption          = \n| office           = [[Department for Education|Shadow Minister for Early Years]]\n| term_start       = 7 January 2020\n| term_end         = \n| predecessor      = [[Tracy Brabin]]\n| leader           = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]<br>[[Sir Keir Starmer]]\n| term_start1      = 9 October 2016\n| predecessor1     = ''Vacant''\n| leader1          = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| successor1       = [[Tracy Brabin]]\n| term_end1        = 26 January 2017\n| office2          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Hampstead and Kilburn (UK Parliament constituency)|Hampstead and Kilburn]]\n| term_start2      = 7 May 2015\n| term_end2        = \n| predecessor2     = [[Glenda Jackson]]\n| successor2       = \n| majority2         = 14,188 (24.7%)\n| office3          = [[Camden London Borough Council]]lor<br />for [[Regent's Park (Camden ward)|Regent's Park]]\n| term_start3      = 6 May 2010\n| term_end3        = 22 May 2014\n| predecessor3     = Theodore Blackwell\n| successor3       = [[Nadia Shah]]\n| birth_name       = Tulip Rizwana Siddiq<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61961 |supp= |page=11776 |date=19 June 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1982|9|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[St Helier, London|St Helier]], [[London Borough of Sutton|Sutton]], [[London]], [[England]]\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| citizenship      = \n| nationality      = British\n| party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| otherparty       = \n| spouse           = {{marriage|Christian William St John Percy|2013}}\n| partner          = \n| relatives        = See [[Sheikh\u2013Wazed family|Sheikh-Wazed family]]\n| children         = 2\n| parents          = {{Plainlist|\n* Shafiq Siddiq (father)\n* [[Sheikh Rehana]] (mother)\n}}\n| residence        = [[West Hampstead]], [[London Borough of Camden|Camden]], London, England\n| alma_mater       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[University College London]]\n* [[King's College London]]\n}}\n| occupation       = \n| profession       = [[Politician]]\n| known_for        = \n| awards           = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| website          = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n\n'''Tulip Rizwana Siddiq MP''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSA}} ({{lang-bn|\u099f\u09bf\u0989\u09b2\u09bf\u09aa \u09b0\u09c7\u099c\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09a8\u09be \u09b8\u09bf\u09a6\u09cd\u09a6\u09c0\u0995}}; born 16 September 1982) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who has served as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Hampstead and Kilburn (UK Parliament constituency)|Hampstead and Kilburn]] since [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]. She was previously the [[Camden London Borough Council]]lor for [[Regent's Park (Camden ward)|Regent's Park]] from 2010 until 2014.\n\n==Early life==\n{{See also|Sheikh\u2013Wazed family}}\nSiddiq is the daughter of economics professor Shafiq Siddiq,<ref name=\"theindependentbd\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=152754:rezwana-siddiq-tulip-among-the-100-powerful-british-bangladeshis-in-uk&catid=95:national&Itemid=141|title=Rezwana Siddiq Tulip, among the 100 powerful British- Bangladeshis in UK|work= |location=Bangladesh|publisher=[[The Independent (Bangladesh)|The Independent]]|date=23 January 2013|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"bdnews241\">{{cite news |last=Pasha|first=Syed Nahas|url=http://www.bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2013/06/19/tulip-weds|title=Tulip Weds|work= |location=London|publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=19 June 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"dhakacourier\">{{cite news |last=Neicho|first=Josh|url=http://www.dhakacourier.com.bd/?p=12853|title=Tulip gets Labour Party nomination in UK|work= |location=Dhaka|publisher=[[Dhaka Courier]]|date=25 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"standard1\">{{cite news |last=Neicho|first=Josh|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/house-of-straw-whos-who-in-labours-new-generation-8196861.html|title=House of Straw... who's who in Labour's new generation|location=London|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=4 October 2012|accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"huffingtonpost\"/><ref name=\"independent2\"/> and [[Sheikh Rehana]],<ref name=\"theindependentbd\"/> who gained political asylum in the UK as a teenager.<ref name=\"independent2\"/> They met when Shafiq Siddiq was studying for a PhD<ref name=\"standard4\">{{cite news |last=Urwin|first=Rosamund|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/tulip-siddiq-go-to-as-many-strip-clubs-as-you-want--i-really-dont-care-are-you-serving-our-people-10177760.html|title=Tulip Siddiq: 'Go to as many strip clubs as you want \u2014 I really don't care. Are you serving our people?'|location=London|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=15 April 2015|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref> and married in Kilburn in 1980.  She has an elder brother, Radwan \"Bobby\" Mujib,<ref name=\"bdnews244\">{{cite news |last=Mahbub|first=Sumon|url=http://www.bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2015/06/16/hasina-listens-to-tulips-maiden-speech-in-uk-parliament|title=Hasina listens to Tulip's maiden speech in UK Parliament|work=| location=London|publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=19 April 2015|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"independent1\"/><ref name=\"bdnews249\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2015/12/21/tulip-siddiq-on-her-first-visit-to-bangladesh-as-a-british-mp|title=Tulip Siddiq on her first visit to Bangladesh as a British MP|work= |location= |publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=21 December 2015|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref> and a younger sister, Rupi.<ref name=\"bdnews245\">{{cite news |last=Khalidi|first=Imrose|url=http://www.bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2015/05/08/tulip-rupa-rushanara-win|title=Tulip, Rupa, Rushanara win|work= |location=Bangladesh|publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=8 May 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> Siddiq was born in [[St Helier Hospital]]<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\">{{cite news |last=Bennett|first=Owen|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/10/19/tulip-siddiq-glenda-jackson-springsteen_n_8330872.html|title=Tulip Siddiq On Glenda Jackson, Why Obama Could Only Fall From The Pedestal, And Why Work Never Stops Even At Zumba Class|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=20 October 2015|accessdate=1 November 2015}}</ref> in [[St Helier, London|St Helier]], [[London]]. When she was 15, the family moved to [[Hampstead]].<ref name=\"standard1\"/> She was raised a Muslim and has said that her \"family embraced multicultural Britain\".<ref name=\"independent4\">{{cite news |last=Siddiq|first=Tulip|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/the-reality-of-being-a-muslim-mp-smear-campaigns-outside-mosques-and-being-told-to-change-my-name-a7013136.html|title=The reality of being a Muslim MP? Smear campaigns outside mosques and being told to change my name|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=4 May 2016|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref> In the heart of North London's Jewish community, she attended [[Passover Seder|seder]] with neighbours and went to [[Limmud]].<ref name=\"labourlist\">{{cite news |last=Siddiq|first=Tulip|url=https://www.labourlist.org/2018/04/tulip-siddiq-party-membership-reflects-a-set-of-values-not-a-safe-space-for-bigots/|title=Tulip Siddiq: Party membership reflects a set of values \u2013 not a safe space for bigots|work= |location= |publisher=Labour List|date=18 April 2018|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref> As a child, she met [[Nelson Mandela]], [[Bill Clinton]] and [[Mother Teresa]],<ref name=\"hamhigh3\">{{cite news |last=Lamden|first=Tim|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/seasonal/election/labour-s-tulip-siddiq-glenda-jackson-is-a-celebrity-i-can-t-compete-with-two-oscars-1-3929031|title=Labour's Tulip Siddiq: 'Glenda Jackson is a celebrity, I can't compete with two Oscars'|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=26 January 2015|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> and her family was invited to the [[White House]].<ref name=\"independent2\">{{cite news |last=Usborne|first=Simon|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tulip-siddiq-the-north-london-labour-candidate-trying-to-improve-the-woeful-diversity-of-westminster-10157378.html|title=Tulip Siddiq: Fighting for Britain's most marginal seat in the shadow of tragedy|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=5 April 2015|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe attended [[The Royal School, Hampstead]],<ref name=\"hamhigh3\"/> before completing her [[undergraduate degree]] in English Literature at [[University College London]] and then a [[master's degree]] at [[King's College London]]. In September 2011, she completed a second master's degree in Politics, Policy and Government.<ref name=\"independent2\"/><ref name=\"bbwhoswho10\">{{cite book |last1=Karim|first1=Mohammed Abdul|last2=Karim|first2=Shahadoth|title=British Bangladeshi Who's Who|url=http://www.bbwhoswho.co.uk/images/who%27%20who%20website%202010.pdf|date=October 2010|publisher=British Bangla Media Group|page=112|isbn= |accessdate=18 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"tulipsiddiq\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tulipsiddiq.com/TulipSiddiq-FortuneGreen1.pdf|title=introducing Tulip Siddiq: your Labour voice in Fortune Green|publisher=Tulip Siddiq|year=2008|accessdate=1 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nHer maternal grandfather is [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]], founding father and the first [[President of Bangladesh]].<ref name=\"independent1\">{{cite news |last=Hensher|first=Philip|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/tulip-siddiq-a-heritage-in-bangadeshi-politics-a-future-in-british-8720884.html|title=Tulip Siddiq: A heritage in Bangadeshi politics, a future in British?|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=19 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> Her mother's elder sister is Prime Minister of Bangladesh [[Sheikh Hasina]].<ref name=\"sylhettimesdigital\"/><ref name=\"aljazeera\">{{cite news |last=Neild|first=Barry|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/01/uk-vote-could-create-cross-border-dynasty-2014113112342206325.html|title=UK vote could create cross-border dynasty|work= |location=Qatar|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=15 January 2014|accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref> \nIn 1975, [[Bangladesh Army]] soldiers stormed Siddiq's mother's home in Bangladesh and [[Assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman|assassinated Siddiq's grandfather, Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]], alongside his three sons<ref name=\"independent2\"/> and 16 other members of his family<ref name=\"hamhigh6\">{{cite news |last=Lamden|first=Tim|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/politics/tulip_siddiq_s_maiden_commons_speech_open_door_immigration_vital_to_hampstead_and_kilburn_1_4115991|title=Tulip Siddiq's maiden Commons speech: 'Open door immigration vital to Hampstead and Kilburn'|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=17 June 2015|accessdate=1 July 2015}}</ref> in a military coup. Siddiq's mother and aunt survived as they were visiting [[Germany]].<ref name=\"independent2\"/>\n\n==Early political career==\nAt the age of 16, Siddiq joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].<ref name=\"standard1\"/> Siddiq's father suffered a stroke, which left him disabled<ref name=\"independent2\"/> and unable to speak for five years.<ref name=\"standard4\"/><ref name=\"independent2\"/> She has cited the [[National Health Service|NHS]] and the care her disabled father received as the reason why she joined.<ref name=\"kilburntimes1\"/> She identified [[Barbara Castle, Baroness Castle of Blackburn|Barbara Castle]] as her political heroine.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\"/> and has described her mother and maternal aunt as \"two very strong feminists\".<ref name=\"independent3\">{{cite news |last=Siddiq|first=Tulip|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tulip-siddiq-the-north-london-labour-candidate-trying-to-improve-the-woeful-diversity-of-westminster-10157378.html|title=Why do we still cling to the belief that most rapes are committed by strangers in dark alleyways?|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=26 November 2015|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe has worked for [[Amnesty International]],<ref name=\"standard4\"/> the [[Greater London Authority]],<ref name=\"labourcouncillor\">{{cite news|url=http://www.labourcouncillor.org.uk/tulip_siddiq|title=Tulip Siddiq \u2013 Camden candidate for 2010 elections|publisher=Labour Councillor|accessdate=18 September 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203011400/http://www.labourcouncillor.org.uk/tulip_siddiq|archivedate=3 December 2011}}</ref> at Philip Gould Associates, the political consultancy firm run by [[New Labour]] strategist [[Philip Gould, Baron Gould of Brookwood|Philip Gould]],<ref name=\"hamhigh3\"/><ref name=\"standard4\"/> [[Save the Children]], and Brunswick, where she worked on corporate social responsibilities initiatives for major British manufacturers, as well as for MPs [[Oona King]], [[Sadiq Khan]] and<ref name=\"bbwhoswho10\"/> [[Harry Cohen]]. Siddiq worked on [[Ed Miliband]]'s campaign to be leader of the Labour Party,<ref name=\"labourcouncillor\"/> and as a special advisor to [[Tessa Jowell]].<ref name=\"standard1\"/> She has campaigned for political parties internationally and, in 2008, campaigned for [[Barack Obama]] in the U.S.<ref name=\"bbwhoswho10\"/>\n\nIn a 2006 by-election, Siddiq stood unsuccessfully for Camden Council.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\"/> In the [[2010 United Kingdom local elections|2010 local government elections]], Siddiq became the first female Bangladeshi councillor for Camden Council,<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite news |last=Wilkinson|first=Michael|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/general-election-2015/11377416/General-Election-2015-the-seats-that-will-decide-who-wins.html|title=9 seats that will decide who wins the General Election|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=30 January 2015|accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref> where she was Cabinet Member for Culture and Communities until [[2014 Camden London Borough Council election|May 2014]].<ref name=\"theguardian1\">{{cite news |last=Siddiq|first=Tulip|url=https://www.theguardian.com/local-government-network/2013/dec/12/library-cuts-volunteers-saved-camdens-libraries|title=How a team of volunteers saved Camden's at risk libraries|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=13 December 2013|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, Siddiq was selected by local party members as the Labour [[prospective parliamentary candidate]] for the [[Hampstead and Kilburn (UK Parliament constituency)|Hampstead and Kilburn constituency]],<ref name=\"kilburntimes1\">{{cite news |last=Beioley|first=Katie|url=http://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/camden_councillor_tulip_siddiq_selected_as_labour_s_prospective_parliamentary_candidate_for_hampstead_and_kilburn_1_2279426|title=Camden councillor Tulip Siddiq selected as Labour's Prospective Parliamentary Candidate for Hampstead and Kilburn|work= |location=Kilburn|publisher=[[Kilburn Times]]|date=15 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"hamhigh2\">{{cite news |last=Beioley|first=Katie|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/tulip_siddiq_selected_as_labour_s_candidate_for_hampstead_and_kilburn_1_2278223|title=Tulip Siddiq selected as Labour's candidate for Hampstead and Kilburn|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=15 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"standard2\">{{cite news |last1=Pettitt|first1=Josh|last2=Watts|first2=Joe|last3=Neicho|first3=Josh |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/labour-selection-contest-for-hampstead-and-kilburn-ends-in-brawl-8708941.html|title=Labour selection contest for Hampstead and Kilburn ends in brawl|location=London|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=15 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"obv\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.obv.org.uk/news-blogs/tulip-siddiq-wining-against-odds|title=Tulip Siddiq: Wining against the odds|work=Operation Black Vote|date=19 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"easterneye\">{{cite news|url=http://www.easterneye.eu/news.html?groupId=15&newsId=2061|title=New Labour candidate Tulip has politics in her blood|work=[[Eastern Eye]]|location=London|date=July 2013|archive-url=https://archive.today/20131201001135/http://www.easterneye.eu/news.html?groupId=15&newsId=2061|archive-date=1 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"indiaweekly\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.indiaweekly.co.uk/news.html?groupId=7&newsId=2061|title=New Labour candidate Tulip has politics in her blood|work= |location=India|publisher=[[India Weekly]]|date= |accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"camdennewjournal3\">{{cite news |last=Osley|first=Richard|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2013/jul/tulip-siddiq-wins-round-one%E2%80%A6-now-real-battle-bid-win-hampstead-and-kilburn-seat-labour|title=Tulip Siddiq wins round one\u2026 now for the real battle in bid to win Hampstead and Kilburn seat for Labour Party|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=18 July 2013|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> despite <!-- Read the source, not in dispute. -->a [[smear campaign]].<ref name=\"hamhigh1\">{{cite news |last=Lamden|first=Tim|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/hampstead_and_kilburn_parliamentary_candidate_tulip_siddiq_hits_back_at_smear_campaign_1_2273210|title=Tulip Siddiq hits back at smear campaign|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=11 July 2013|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> During 2013 and 2014, she campaigned against the proposed high-speed railway expansion [[High Speed 2]],<ref name=\"camdennewjournal5\">{{cite news |last=Foot|first=Tom|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2014/feb/hs2-another-crammed-public-meeting-another-legion-opponents-high-speed-rail-chaos|title=HS2: Another crammed public meeting, another legion of opponents to high speed rail chaos|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=13 February 2014|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> and high pay day lender charges on [[Kilburn High Road]].<ref name=\"kilburntimes1\"/> She also campaigned in support of local services, such as to keep Belsize Fire Station open,<ref name=\"camdennewjournal2\">{{cite news |last=Foot|first=Tom|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2013/jun/meeting-told-how-mayor-boris%E2%80%99s-proposals-axe-fire-stations-will-threaten-safety-high-r|title=Meeting told how Mayor Boris's proposals to axe fire stations will threaten safety of 'high-rise towers'|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=6 June 2013|accessdate=12 January 2015}}</ref> to improve disabled access at [[West Hampstead tube station]]<ref name=\"camdennewjournal6\">{{cite news |last=Hutton|first=Alice|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/West-Hampstead-lift|title=West Hampstead tube station must get lift, campaigners cry|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=24 September 2014|accessdate=12 January 2015}}</ref> and to save the Swiss Cottage post office.<ref name=\"camdennewjournal4\">{{cite news |last=Foot|first=Tom|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2013/sep/plea-save-swiss-cottage-post-office-gets-louder|title=Plea to save Swiss Cottage post office gets louder|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=19 September 2013|accessdate=12 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nIn the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], Siddiq won the Hampstead and Kilburn seat with 23,977 votes, with a turnout of 67.3%.<ref name=\"bdnews246\">{{cite news |last=Pasha|first=Syed Nahas|url=http://www.bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2015/05/08/ive-learned-politics-from-my-aunt-sheikh-hasina-tulip-siddiq|title=New British MP Tulip Siddiq says she learned politics from aunt Sheikh Hasina|work= |location=London|publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=8 May 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"hamhigh4\">{{cite news |last=Beioley|first=Katie|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/home/election-2015/tulip_siddiq_hampstead_and_kilburn_is_my_home_and_i_m_so_proud_to_represent_it_1_4065675|title=Tulip Siddiq: 'Hampstead and Kilburn is my home and I'm so proud to represent it'|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=8 May 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> The seat was previously held by [[Glenda Jackson]].<ref name=\"camdennewjournal7\">{{cite news |last=Osley|first=Richard|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2015/may/full-story-tulip-siddiq-defends-hampstead-and-kilburn-parliamentary-seat-labour|title=Full story: Tulip Siddiq defends Hampstead and Kilburn parliamentary seat for Labour|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=8 May 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> The seat had previously been the second most marginal in the country after Jackson retained the seat by just 42 votes in 2010<ref name=\"thejc1\">{{cite news |last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/135987/election-2015-tulip-siddiq-secures-hampstead-and-kilburn-labour|title=Election 2015: Tulip Siddiq secures Hampstead and Kilburn for Labour|newspaper=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=8 May 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> and was billed in 2015 as the UK's most marginal general election contest.<ref name=\"kilburntimes2\">{{cite news |last=Beioley|first=Katie|url=http://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/home/election-2015/hampstead_and_kilburn_general_election_2015_polling_day_in_england_s_most_marginal_seat_1_4064112|title=Hampstead and Kilburn general election 2015: Polling day in England's most marginal seat|work= |location=Kilburn|publisher=[[Kilburn Times]]|date=7 May 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> In June 2015, Siddiq was appointed a vice-chair of the [[All-Party Parliamentary Group against Antisemitism]].<ref name=\"hamhigh5\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/politics/hampstead_and_kilburn_mp_tulip_siddiq_praised_for_early_role_tackling_anti_semitism_1_4105621|title=Hampstead and Kilburn MP Tulip Siddiq praised for early role tackling anti-Semitism|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=9 June 2015|accessdate=1 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"thejc2\">{{cite news | last1=Streeting|first1=Wes|last2=Siddiq|first2=Tulip|url=https://www.thejc.com/comment/comment/wes-streeting-and-tulip-siddiq-1.436660|title=We've heard your anxieties loud and clear|newspaper=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=24 April 2017|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref> She is also a member of the [[Women and Equalities Committee|Women and Equalities Select Committee]].<ref name=\"parliament\">{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/tulip-siddiq/4518|title=Tulip Siddiq MP|publisher=UK Parliament|date= |accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref> In the same month, she was one of 36 Labour MPs to nominate [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as a candidate in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Labour leadership election]],<ref name=\"newstatesman\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/06/who-nominated-who-2015-labour-leadership-election|title=Who nominated who for the 2015 Labour leadership election?|magazine=[[New Statesman]]|date=15 June 2015|accessdate=8 September 2015}}</ref> although she later supported [[Andy Burnham]].<ref name=\"standard5\">{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/why-labours-rising-star-tulip-siddiq-is-taking-maternity-leave-a3159106.html|title=Labour's rising star Tulip Siddiq on why maternity leave shouldn't be a problem in politics|location=London|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=18 January 2016|accessdate=18 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Siddiq along with [[Keir Starmer]] and [[Catherine West]] wrote a letter to British Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] seeking urgent action to address the [[Refugees of the Syrian Civil War|refugee crisis]] due to the [[Syrian Civil War]].<ref name=\"theguardian3\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/04/britain-best-placed-to-lead-international-response-to-the-refugee-crisis|title=Britain best placed to lead international response to the refugee crisis|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=4 September 2015|accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"bdnews247\">{{cite news |last=Pasha|first=Syed Nahas|url=http://www.bdnews24.com/world/2015/09/05/tulip-siddiq-urges-pm-cameron-to-take-urgent-action-to-address-refugee-crisis-in-europe|title=Tulip Siddiq urges PM Cameron to take urgent action to address refugee crisis in Europe|work= |location=London|publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=5 September 2015|accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"prothom-alo1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.en.prothom-alo.com/international/news/78227/Tulip-seeks-action-to-end-refugee-crisis|title=Tulip seeks action to end refugee crisis|location=Dhaka|newspaper=[[Prothom Alo]]|date=5 September 2015|accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref> In the same month, she was appointed Permanent Private Secretary to the Shadow Minister for Culture, Media and Sport, [[Michael Dugher]].<ref name=\"bdnews248\">{{cite news |last=Pasha|first=Syed Nahas|url=http://www.bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2015/09/26/tulip-siddiq-named-for-labour-shadow-job|title=Tulip Siddiq named for Labour 'shadow' job|work= |location=London|publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=26 September 2015|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"dhakatribune1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2015/sep/27/tulip-made-shadow-state-minister|title=Tulip made shadow state minister|location=Dhaka|newspaper=[[Dhaka Tribune]]|date=27 September 2015|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"newsnextbd\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.newsnextbd.com/tulip-made-shadow-minister-in-britain/|title=Tulip made shadow minister in Britain |work= |location=Bangladesh|publisher=Newsnext Bangladesh|date=27 September 2015|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"thedailystar2\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/tulip-siddiq-shadow-cabinet-labour-party-148966|title=Tulip Siddiq in shadow cabinet of Labour Party|location=Bangladesh|newspaper=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|date=29 September 2015|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref> In November 2015, she campaigned against changes to junior doctor contracts.<ref name=\"camdennewjournal8\">{{cite news |last=Osley|first=Richard|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/tuliphunt|title=New MP Tulip Siddiq challenges Health Secretary Jeremy Hunt to meet frustrated junior doctors at Royal Free|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=5 November 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> In the same month, Siddiq's maiden speech in Parliament was judged one of the top seven from 2015's intake of MPs by the BBC.<ref name=\"hamhigh7\">{{cite news |last=Roberts|first=Rachel|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/politics/hampstead_and_kilburn_mp_tulip_siddiq_s_maiden_speech_judged_in_top_seven_by_bbc_1_4295775|title=Hampstead and Kilburn MP Tulip Siddiq's maiden speech judged in top seven by BBC|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=3 November 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> In October 2016, she was appointed as Shadow Education Minister in the [[Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn|Labour Party's frontbench in Parliament]],<ref name=\"hamhigh9\">{{cite news |last=Banks|first=Emily|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/politics/tulip-siddiq-given-early-years-role-in-corbyn-s-shadow-cabinet-1-4728884|title=Tulip Siddiq given early years role in Corbyn's shadow cabinet|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=9 October 2016|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"thedailystar4\">{{cite news |last=Liton|first=Shakhawat|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/city/tulip-gives-birth-girl-1206841|title=Tulip Siddiq and our MPs|location=Bangladesh|newspaper=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|date=2 February 2016|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref> taking on the childcare and early years education brief and working with [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]] [[Angela Rayner]].<ref name=\"camdennewjournal11\">{{cite news |last=Osley|first=Richard|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/tulip-siddiq-shadow-corbyn|title=Hampstead and Kilburn MP Tulip Siddiq accepts education job in Jeremy Corbyn's team at House of Commons|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=9 October 2016|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Siddiq supported a motion in Parliament for the UK to withdraw support for the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]].<ref name=\"5pillarsuk\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.5pillarsuk.com/2016/11/01/which-muslim-mps-voted-to-stop-arms-sales-to-saudi-arabia/|title=Which Muslim MPs voted to stop arms sales to Saudi Arabia?|work= |location= |publisher=5Pillars|date=1 November 2016|accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref> In January 2017, she resigned from the Labour frontbench over Labour's [[three-line whip]], to vote against triggering [[Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union]]. Siddiq stated that because around 75% of her Hampstead and Kilburn constituency voted to remain in the [[European Union]] as one of the top 10 remain areas, she could not \"reconcile\" herself with Labour's position.<ref name=\"theguardian4\">{{cite news |last=Elgot|first=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jan/26/labour-mp-tulip-siddiq-resigns-from-frontbench-over-article-50-vote |title=Labour MP Tulip Siddiq resigns from frontbench over article 50 vote|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=26 January 2017|accessdate=5 April 2017}}</ref> Siddiq won an endorsement from Camden for Europe, [[Open Britain]] and [[Best for Britain]], due to her decision to vote against Article 50.<ref name=\"camdennewjournal13\">{{cite news |last=Osley|first=Richard|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/article/hampstead-and-kilburn-gina-miller-teams-up-with-tulip-siddiq-as-election-race-gets-tactical|title=UKIP target anti-Brexit Tulip Siddiq by\u2026 not standing a candidate against her|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=18 May 2017|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|general election]], Siddiq retained her seat with an increased majority of 15,560.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000727|title=Hampstead & Kilburn parliamentary constituency - Election 2017|work=[[BBC News]]|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"standard6\">{{cite news |last=De Peyer|first=Robin|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/hampstead-and-kilburn-election-results-who-is-the-mp-for-the-constituency-after-the-general-election-a3547426.html|title=Hampstead and Kilburn election results: Labour's Tulip Siddiq wins north west London constituency|location=London|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"camdennewjournal12\">{{cite news |last=Osley|first=Richard|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/article/neck-and-neck-tulip-siddiq-holds-hampstead-and-kilburn-with-five-figure-majority|title=Neck and neck? Tulip Siddiq holds Hampstead and Kilburn with five-figure majority|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"standard7\">{{cite news |last=Kirk|first=Tristan|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/general-election-2017-may-underestimated-the-british-public-says-tulip-siddiq-a3560716.html|title=Theresa May 'underestimated the British public' says Tulip Siddiq|location=London|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Siddiq called for businesses to \"address imbalance\" in the employment of BAME individuals to improve the diversity of its workforce.<ref name=\"voice-online\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/do-british-businesses-employ-enough-bame-individuals|title=Do British businesses employ enough BAME individuals?|work= |location= |publisher=[[The Voice (British newspaper)|The Voice]]|date=30 August 2017|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref> In September 2017, Siddiq was appointed as Chair of the new Childcare and Early Education All-Party Parliamentary Group (APPG).<ref name=\"nurseryworld\">{{cite news |last=Morton|first=Katy|url=http://www.nurseryworld.co.uk/nursery-world/news/1162159/tulip-siddiq-named-chair-of-early-years-appg|title=Tulip Siddiq named chair of early years APPG|work= |location= |publisher=[[Nursery World]]|date=7 September 2017|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref> In the same month, Siddiq wrote to the [[Home Office]] to ask for children's passports to be amended to contain both their parents' names to avoid confusion at airports and borders. Siddiq had been stopped with her daughter at UK border control whilst returning from a family holiday until her husband joined them, because she did not have the same surname in her passport as her child.<ref name=\"theguardian6\">{{cite news |last=Elgot|first=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/sep/06/mp-stopped-at-border-over-daughters-name-urges-passports-reform|title=MP stopped at border over daughter's name urges passport reform|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=6 September 2017|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"standard8\">{{cite news |last=Grafton-Green|first=Patrick|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/mp-tulip-siddiq-reveals-she-was-stopped-by-border-control-over-her-daughters-name-a3629391.html|title=MP Tulip Siddiq reveals she was stopped by border control over her daughter's name|location=London|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=7 September 2017|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"refinery29\">{{cite news |last=Gill|first=Natalie|url=http://www.refinery29.uk/2017/09/171196/mothers-surnames-childrens-passports-marriage-tulip-siddiq|title=Mothers Surnames Childrens Passports \u2013 Tulip Siddiq MP|work= |location= |publisher=[[Refinery29]]|date=7 September 2017|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref> In November 2017, whilst campaigning for the release of her constituent, the British-Iranian citizen [[Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe]], who is detained in Iran, she was asked by [[Alex Thomson (journalist)|Alex Thomson]] of ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' and [[ITN]] about using her family ties to the Bangladeshi government, led by her aunt, in order to liberate British Bangladeshi barrister Ahmad bin Quasem, who is thought to have been abducted by state security forces in Bangladesh. The programme's editor, [[Ben de Pear]], complained about Siddiq's \"threatening behaviour\" to a pregnant producer, while Siddiq complained to the police about her interlocutors.<ref name=\"telegraph2\">{{cite news |last1=Jamieson|first1=Sophie|last2=Hope|first2=Christopher|last3=Horton|first3=Helena|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/28/labour-mp-makes-threatening-remark-pregnant-journalist/|title=Labour MP Tulip Siddiq makes 'threatening' remark to pregnant journalist |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=29 November 2017|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"theguardian7\">{{cite news |last=Grierson|first=Jamie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/29/channel-4-news-complains-to-labour-over-tulip-siddiqs-threat|title=Tulip Siddiq apologises for remark to pregnant Channel 4 producer|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=29 November 2017|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"independent5\">{{cite news |last=Peck|first=Tom|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-mp-nazanin-zaghari-ratcliff-free-iran-bangladesh-tulip-siddiq-aunt-prime-minister-sheikh-a8081656.html|title=Labour MP leading campaign to free British citizen in Iran avoids requests to help British man in Bangladesh|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=29 November 2017|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref> She later apologised in a statement to the producer,<!-- who strictly speaking works for ITN, rather than Channel 4. --> Daisy Ayliffe, for the offence caused.<ref name=\"theguardian7\" />\n\nIn May 2018, Siddiq supported an [[Equal pay for equal work|equal pay]] campaign aimed at building pressure on employers.<ref name=\"dhakatribune2\">{{cite news |last=Khanna|first=Aditi|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2015/sep/27/tulip-made-shadow-state-minister|title=Tulip Siddiq backs equal pay campaign in UK|location=Dhaka|newspaper=[[Dhaka Tribune]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref> In the same month, Siddiq described the actions of the [[Israel Defense Forces|Israeli military]] during [[2018 Gaza border protests|demonstrations on the Gaza border]] as \"unjustified\" and \"inhumane\". She said: \"I condemn without reservation these violations of international law and human rights by Israel... The protest has been twofold - to highlight the shocking conditions which Palestinians are forced to live in and to demand their [[Palestinian right of return|right to return]] to their homes...\"<ref name=\"thejc5\">{{cite news |last=Harpin|first=Lee|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-mp-tulip-siddiq-explains-backing-hamas-call-for-palestinians-to-return-to-their-homes-in-israel-1.464207|title=Labour MP explains her call for Palestinians to 'return to their homes' in Israel|newspaper=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=16 May 2018|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> In August 2018, Tulip Siddiq joined international calls for her aunt's government to release Bangladeshi photographer [[Shahidul Alam]], who had been jailed after reporting about protests by schoolchildren over road safety problems, and had subsequently stated he was tortured.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/mp-urges-aunt-to-release-bangladesh-photographer-w9tgs0svw|title=MP urges aunt to release Bangladesh photographer Shahidul Alam|last=|first=|date=28 August 2018|work=The Times|access-date=5 September 2018|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news/world/british-mp-tulip-siddiq-seeks-release-of-photographer-shahidul-alam-1625617|title=Tulip calls for release of Shahidul|last=|first=|date=29 August 2018|work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=5 September 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\nSiddiq was a board member of West Euston Partnership and is governor of the Camden and Islington [[NHS Foundation Trust]].<ref name=\"sylhettimesdigital\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://sylhettimesdigital.co.uk/miliband-praises-young-british-bangladeshi-labour-hopefuls/|title=Miliband praises young British Bangladeshi Labour hopefuls|work= |location= |publisher=The Sylhet Times|date=20 January 2010|accessdate=18 September 2011}}</ref> She served as national BAME (Black, Asian and Minority Ethnic) Officer for [[Young Labour (United Kingdom)|Young Labour]] and Women's Officer for [[London Labour Party|London]] Young Labour. She is an executive board member of [[Unite the Union]], a member of the [[Co-operative Party]], a fellow of the [[Royal Society of Arts]] and is also a member of the Commonwealth Journalists Association (UK).<ref name=\"bbwhoswho10\"/> She also oversaw Camden's engagement with the [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London Olympics]], which saw the launch of three legacy schemes to encourage more physical activities, Camden Sports Academy, School and Community Games, and Pro-Active Ambassadors.<ref name=\"camdennewjournal1\">{{cite news |last=Barnett|first=Steve|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2011/jan/2012-sports-scheme-olympic-hopefuls-support-gold-challenge-initiative-swiss-cottage-le|title=2012 sports scheme \u2013 Olympic hopefuls support Gold Challenge initiative at Swiss Cottage Leisure Centre|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=27 January 2011|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nSiddiq served two years as a [[school governor]] at Beckford Primary School and Richard Cobden Primary School<ref name=\"rcobden\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rcobden.camden.sch.uk/governors_lists.html|title=List of Governors|publisher=Richard Cobden Primary School|date= |accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref> and is a current governor at the Working Men's College in Camden.<ref name=\"wmcollege\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wmcollege.ac.uk/pages/working-mens-college-governors.aspx|title=Working Men's College Governors|publisher=Working Men's College|date= |accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> As of January 2014, Siddiq supports a number of organisations in Hampstead and Kilburn, including school governor roles at Emmanuel Primary School<ref name=\"emmanuel\">{{cite web |url= http://www.emmanuel.camden.sch.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Governors-of-Emmanuel-School.pdf|title=Membership of the Governing Body|publisher=Emmanual Church of England Primary School|date= |accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> and Granville Plus Nursery<ref name=\"granvilleplus\">{{cite web |url=http://www.granvilleplus.org.uk/Governors/|title=Governors|publisher=Granville Plus Nursery School|date= |accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> as well as being a trustee of the Camden Arts Centre.<ref name=\"camdenartscentre\">{{cite web |url=http://www.camdenartscentre.org/contact|title=Contact|publisher=Camden Arts Centre|date= |accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> She has also written for ''[[Hampstead and Highgate Express]]''<ref name=\"bbwhoswho10\"/> as a foreign correspondent, primarily covering the [[Elections in the United States|U.S. elections]].\n\n==Recognition==\nIn January 2013, Siddiq was named in the \"[[British Bangladeshi Power & Inspiration 100]]\".<ref name=\"theindependentbd\"/> In December 2014, she was named by ''[[The Guardian]]'' as \"one to watch\" in British politics.<ref name=\"theguardian2\">{{cite news |last=Cadwalladr|first=Carole|url=https://www.theguardian.com/local-government-network/2013/dec/12/library-cuts-volunteers-saved-camdens-libraries|title=Rising stars of 2015: politician Dan Jarvis|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=28 December 2014|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> In April 2015, ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' described her as one of the \"rising stars\" of the Labour Party.<ref name=\"thesundaytimes\">{{cite news |last1=Shipman|first1=Tim|last2=Woolf|first2=Marie|url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/focus/article1542759.ece|title=Get-ahead gang in a hurry|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=12 April 2015|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"bdnews243\">{{cite news |last=Pasha|first=Syed Nahas|url=http://ww.bdnews24.com/world/2015/04/19/tulip-siddiqs-determined-campaign|title=Tulip Siddiq's determined campaign|work= |location=London|publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=19 April 2015|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSiddiq is a [[Muslim]]<ref name=\"aljazeera\"/> but said she is \"more cultural than religious\".<ref name=\"hamhigh3\"/> In 2013,<ref name=\"thedailystar1\">{{cite news |last=Karim|first=Rezaul|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/beta2/news/on-official-trip-for-nieces-wedding/|title=On official trip, for niece's wedding \u2013 PM flies to London today en route to Belarus|location=Bangladesh|newspaper=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|date=4 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> Siddiq married Christian William St John Percy (born 1984),<ref name=\"telegraphindia\">{{cite news |last=Roy|first=Amit|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1130804/jsp/7days/17192386.jsp|title=Tulip gets the ticket|location=India|newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|Telegraph India]]|date=4 August 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> who is a Cambridge-educated<ref name=\"bangladeshchronicle2\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.bangladeshchronicle.net/index.php/2013/07/he-speaks-chinese-and-is-learning-bangla/|title=He speaks Chinese and is learning Bangla|work= |location=Bangladesh|publisher=The Bangladesh Chronicle|date=8 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> company director<ref name=\"tribuneindia\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/world/b-desh-pm-s-niece-on-verge-of-becoming-british-mp/69775.html|title=B'desh PM's niece on verge of becoming British MP|location=India|work=[[The Tribune (India)|The Tribune]]|date=20 April 2015|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref> and strategy consultant with a background in the British civil service.<ref name=\"bangladeshchronicle2\"/> Siddiq lives in a flat on [[Finchley Road]],<ref name=\"hamhigh4\"/> [[West Hampstead]], London with her husband.<ref name=\"kilburntimes1\"/><ref name=\"standard2\"/><ref name=\"bangladeshchronicle1\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.bangladeshchronicle.net/index.php/2013/06/tulip-weds/|title=So what's his full name?|work= |location=Bangladesh|publisher=The Bangladesh Chronicle|date=8 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> In April 2016, Siddiq gave birth to a daughter at the [[Royal Free Hospital]] in Hampstead.<ref name=\"hamhigh8\">{{cite news |last=Roberts|first=Rachel|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/hampstead_and_kilburn_mp_tulip_siddiq_gives_birth_to_her_first_baby_1_4488924|title=Hampstead and Kilburn MP Tulip Siddiq gives birth to her first baby|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=9 April 2016|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"camdennewjournal10\">{{cite news |last=Osley|first=Richard|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/azalea-percy|title=Hampstead and Kilburn MP Tulip Siddiq gives birth to first child|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=9 April 2016|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"bdnews2410\">{{cite news |last= |first=|url=http://www.bdnews24.com/politics/2016/04/09/tulip-siddiq-gives-birth-to-a-baby-girl|title=Tulip Siddiq gives birth to a baby girl|work= |location= |publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=9 April 2016|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"prothom-alo2\">{{cite news |url=http://www.en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/101137/Tulip-Siddiq-blessed-with-daughter|title=Tulip Siddiq blessed with daughter|location=Dhaka|newspaper=[[Prothom Alo]]|date=9 April 2016|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"thedailystar3\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/city/tulip-gives-birth-girl-1206841|title=Hasina becomes great-aunt|location=Bangladesh|newspaper=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|date=10 April 2016|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref> Tulip Siddiq's husband Christian William St John Percy is a [[Christians|Christian]] by [[religion]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.elle.com/uk/life-and-culture/culture/a20741768/this-is-modern-love/ |title = Modern Love: Meet the Couples Redefining What It Looks Like in 2018|date = 18 May 2018}}</ref> Siddiq herself told in an interview that \"I\u2019m Muslim and Chris is Christian, but we\u2019ve just maintained our own culture and religion by taking an interest in each other\u2019s. We\u2019re teaching our daughter both and then she\u2019ll choose when she\u2019s older. She\u2019ll do Muslim and Bangladeshi cultural things with me, but she also knows what church is like.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.elle.com/uk/life-and-culture/culture/a20741768/this-is-modern-love/ |title = Modern Love: Meet the Couples Redefining What It Looks Like in 2018|date = 18 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe gave birth to a son in January 2019.<ref name=\"DelayedBirth\">{{cite web |title=MP who delayed birth of son accuses Tories over proxy vote delay |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jan/21/mp-who-delayed-birth-of-son-accuses-tories-over-proxy-vote-delay |website=The Guardian |accessdate=21 January 2019 |date=21 January 2019}}</ref> Two days before the birth she attended the Commons in a wheelchair, for a critical [[Brexit]]-related [[Meaningful vote|vote]].<ref name=\"DelayedBirth\" /> On 29 January, following a constitutional change, she became the first ever MP to vote by proxy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-47061992/labour-mp-tulip-siddiq-allowed-proxy-votes-for-brexit|work=BBC News|title=Labour MP Tulip Siddiq allowed proxy votes for Brexit|date=30 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nSiddiq's daughter attends a Jewish nursery. Since becoming an MP, Siddiq has spoken at [[Limmud]] and attends synagogue events.<ref name=\"thejc4\">{{cite news |last=Harpin|first=Lee|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/tulip-siddiq-i-have-been-active-in-speaking-out-against-antisemitism-1.438440|title=Tulip Siddiq: 'I have been active in speaking out against antisemitism'|newspaper=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=12 May 2017|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> In April 2019, Siddiq announced that a relative died in the [[2019 Sri Lanka Easter bombings]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Victims of Sri Lanka terror attacks revealed: who were they? |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/victims-of-sri-lanka-terror-attacks-revealed-who-were-they |work=SBS News |date=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[British Bangladeshi]]\n*[[List of British Bangladeshis]]\n*[[List of ethnic minority politicians in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n*{{Official website|http://www.tulipsiddiq.com/}}\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=tulip-siddiq/4518 |publicwhip=Tulip_Siddiq |theywork=tulip_siddiq}}\n*[http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/tulip-siddiq/ Tulip Siddiq] on ''[[Huffington Post]]''\n*[http://democracy.camden.gov.uk/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=217 Tulip Siddiq] on Camden Council\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* {{cite news | last = Siddiq | first = Tulip | title = How to engage ethnic minorities with democracy | url =  http://compassonline.org.uk/news/item.asp?n=4522 | work = Compass | date = 18 May 2009}}\n* {{cite news | last = Siddiq | first = Tulip | title = The pessimism of Baroness Warsi | url = http://labourlist.org/tulip-siddiq-the-pessimism-of-baroness-warsi | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101219204142/http://labourlist.org/tulip-siddiq-the-pessimism-of-baroness-warsi | url-status = dead | archive-date = 19 December 2010 | work = Labour List | date = 3 October 2010}}\n* {{cite news | last = Siddiq | first = Tulip | title = How I'm trying to stop library cuts in Camden | url = http://liberalconspiracy.org/2011/03/08/how-ive-tried-to-stop-library-cuts-in-camden/ | work = Liberal Conspiracy | date = 8 March 2011}}\n{{col-2}}\n* {{cite news | last = Siddiq | first = Tulip | title = How a team of volunteers saved Camden's at risk libraries | url = https://www.theguardian.com/local-government-network/2013/dec/12/library-cuts-volunteers-saved-camdens-libraries | work = [[The Guardian]] | date = 13 December 2013}}\n* {{cite news | last = Lamden | first = Tim | title = Hampstead and Kilburn general election 2015: Labour candidate Tulip Siddiq's final word | url = http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/home/election-2015/hampstead_and_kilburn_general_election_2015_labour_candidate_tulip_siddiq_s_final_word_1_4063113 | work = [[Ham & High]] | date = 7 May 2015}}\n* {{cite news | last = Bennett | first = Owen | title =  Tulip Siddiq On Glenda Jackson, Why Obama Could Only Fall From The Pedestal, And Why Work Never Stops Even At Zumba Class | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/10/19/tulip-siddiq-glenda-jackson-springsteen_n_8330872.html | work = [[The Huffington Post]] | date = 20 October 2015}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Glenda Jackson]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n |title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Hampstead and Kilburn (UK Parliament constituency)|Hampstead and Kilburn]]\n |years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{London Labour Party MPs}}\n{{Sheikh Mujibur Rahman}}\n{{Sheikh Hasina}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Siddiq, Tulip}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English Muslims]]\n[[Category:English people of Bangladeshi descent]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Camden]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Bangladeshi descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n[[Category:School governors]]\n[[Category:People from Mitcham]]\n[[Category:People educated at The Royal School, Hampstead]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Sheikh Mujibur Rahman family]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Tulip Siddiq\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n\n|honorific-prefix =\n\n| image            = Official portrait of Tulip Siddiq crop 2.jpg\n| caption          = \n| office           = [[Department for Education|Shadow Minister for Early Years]]\n| term_start       = 7 January 2020\n| term_end         = \n| predecessor      = [[Tracy Brabin]]\n| leader           = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]<br>[[Sir Keir Starmer]]\n| term_start1      = 9 October 2016\n| predecessor1     = ''Vacant''\n| leader1          = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| successor1       = [[Tracy Brabin]]\n| term_end1        = 26 January 2017\n| office2          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Hampstead and Kilburn (UK Parliament constituency)|Hampstead and Kilburn]]\n| term_start2      = 7 May 2015\n| term_end2        = \n| predecessor2     = [[Glenda Jackson]]\n| successor2       = \n| majority2         = 14,188 (24.7%)\n| office3          = [[Camden London Borough Council]]lor<br />for [[Regent's Park (Camden ward)|Regent's Park]]\n| term_start3      = 6 May 2010\n| term_end3        = 22 May 2014\n| predecessor3     = Theodore Blackwell\n| successor3       = [[Nadia Shah]]\n| birth_name       = Tulip Rizwana Siddiq<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61961 |supp= |page=11776 |date=19 June 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1982|9|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[St Helier, London|St Helier]], [[London Borough of Sutton|Sutton]], [[London]], [[England]]\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| citizenship      = \n| nationality      = British\n| party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| otherparty       = \n| spouse           = {{marriage|Christian William St John Percy|2013}}\n| partner          = \n| relatives        = See [[Sheikh\u2013Wazed family|Sheikh-Wazed family]]\n| children         = 2\n| parents          = {{Plainlist|\n* Shafiq Siddiq (father)\n* [[Sheikh Rehana]] (mother)\n}}\n| residence        = [[West Hampstead]], [[London Borough of Camden|Camden]], London, England\n| alma_mater       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[University College London]]\n* [[King's College London]]\n}}\n| occupation       = \n| profession       = [[Politician]]\n| known_for        = \n| awards           = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| website          = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n\n'''Tulip Rizwana Siddiq MP''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSA}} ({{lang-bn|\u099f\u09bf\u0989\u09b2\u09bf\u09aa \u09b0\u09c7\u099c\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09a8\u09be \u09b8\u09bf\u09a6\u09cd\u09a6\u09c0\u0995}}; born 16 September 1982) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who has served as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Hampstead and Kilburn (UK Parliament constituency)|Hampstead and Kilburn]] since [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]. She was previously the [[Camden London Borough Council]]lor for [[Regent's Park (Camden ward)|Regent's Park]] from 2010 until 2014.\n\n==Early life==\n{{See also|Sheikh\u2013Wazed family}}\nSiddiq is the daughter of economics professor Shafiq Siddiq,<ref name=\"theindependentbd\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=152754:rezwana-siddiq-tulip-among-the-100-powerful-british-bangladeshis-in-uk&catid=95:national&Itemid=141|title=Rezwana Siddiq Tulip, among the 100 powerful British- Bangladeshis in UK|work= |location=Bangladesh|publisher=[[The Independent (Bangladesh)|The Independent]]|date=23 January 2013|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"bdnews241\">{{cite news |last=Pasha|first=Syed Nahas|url=http://www.bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2013/06/19/tulip-weds|title=Tulip Weds|work= |location=London|publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=19 June 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"dhakacourier\">{{cite news |last=Neicho|first=Josh|url=http://www.dhakacourier.com.bd/?p=12853|title=Tulip gets Labour Party nomination in UK|work= |location=Dhaka|publisher=[[Dhaka Courier]]|date=25 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"standard1\">{{cite news |last=Neicho|first=Josh|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/house-of-straw-whos-who-in-labours-new-generation-8196861.html|title=House of Straw... who's who in Labour's new generation|location=London|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=4 October 2012|accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"huffingtonpost\"/><ref name=\"independent2\"/> and [[Sheikh Rehana]],<ref name=\"theindependentbd\"/> who gained political asylum in the UK as a teenager.<ref name=\"independent2\"/> They met when Shafiq Siddiq was studying for a PhD<ref name=\"standard4\">{{cite news |last=Urwin|first=Rosamund|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/tulip-siddiq-go-to-as-many-strip-clubs-as-you-want--i-really-dont-care-are-you-serving-our-people-10177760.html|title=Tulip Siddiq: 'Go to as many strip clubs as you want \u2014 I really don't care. Are you serving our people?'|location=London|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=15 April 2015|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref> and married in Kilburn in 1980.  She has an elder brother, Radwan \"Bobby\" Mujib,<ref name=\"bdnews244\">{{cite news |last=Mahbub|first=Sumon|url=http://www.bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2015/06/16/hasina-listens-to-tulips-maiden-speech-in-uk-parliament|title=Hasina listens to Tulip's maiden speech in UK Parliament|work=| location=London|publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=19 April 2015|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"independent1\"/><ref name=\"bdnews249\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2015/12/21/tulip-siddiq-on-her-first-visit-to-bangladesh-as-a-british-mp|title=Tulip Siddiq on her first visit to Bangladesh as a British MP|work= |location= |publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=21 December 2015|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref> and a younger sister, Rupi.<ref name=\"bdnews245\">{{cite news |last=Khalidi|first=Imrose|url=http://www.bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2015/05/08/tulip-rupa-rushanara-win|title=Tulip, Rupa, Rushanara win|work= |location=Bangladesh|publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=8 May 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> Siddiq was born in [[St Helier Hospital]]<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\">{{cite news |last=Bennett|first=Owen|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/10/19/tulip-siddiq-glenda-jackson-springsteen_n_8330872.html|title=Tulip Siddiq On Glenda Jackson, Why Obama Could Only Fall From The Pedestal, And Why Work Never Stops Even At Zumba Class|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=20 October 2015|accessdate=1 November 2015}}</ref> in [[St Helier, London|St Helier]], [[London]]. When she was 15, the family moved to [[Hampstead]].<ref name=\"standard1\"/> She was raised a Muslim and has said that her \"family embraced multicultural Britain\".<ref name=\"independent4\">{{cite news |last=Siddiq|first=Tulip|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/the-reality-of-being-a-muslim-mp-smear-campaigns-outside-mosques-and-being-told-to-change-my-name-a7013136.html|title=The reality of being a Muslim MP? Smear campaigns outside mosques and being told to change my name|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=4 May 2016|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref> In the heart of North London's Jewish community, she attended [[Passover Seder|seder]] with neighbours and went to [[Limmud]].<ref name=\"labourlist\">{{cite news |last=Siddiq|first=Tulip|url=https://www.labourlist.org/2018/04/tulip-siddiq-party-membership-reflects-a-set-of-values-not-a-safe-space-for-bigots/|title=Tulip Siddiq: Party membership reflects a set of values \u2013 not a safe space for bigots|work= |location= |publisher=Labour List|date=18 April 2018|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref> As a child, she met [[Nelson Mandela]], [[Bill Clinton]] and [[Mother Teresa]],<ref name=\"hamhigh3\">{{cite news |last=Lamden|first=Tim|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/seasonal/election/labour-s-tulip-siddiq-glenda-jackson-is-a-celebrity-i-can-t-compete-with-two-oscars-1-3929031|title=Labour's Tulip Siddiq: 'Glenda Jackson is a celebrity, I can't compete with two Oscars'|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=26 January 2015|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> and her family was invited to the [[White House]].<ref name=\"independent2\">{{cite news |last=Usborne|first=Simon|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tulip-siddiq-the-north-london-labour-candidate-trying-to-improve-the-woeful-diversity-of-westminster-10157378.html|title=Tulip Siddiq: Fighting for Britain's most marginal seat in the shadow of tragedy|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=5 April 2015|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe attended [[The Royal School, Hampstead]],<ref name=\"hamhigh3\"/> before completing her [[undergraduate degree]] in English Literature at [[University College London]] and then a [[master's degree]] at [[King's College London]]. In September 2011, she completed a second master's degree in Politics, Policy and Government.<ref name=\"independent2\"/><ref name=\"bbwhoswho10\">{{cite book |last1=Karim|first1=Mohammed Abdul|last2=Karim|first2=Shahadoth|title=British Bangladeshi Who's Who|url=http://www.bbwhoswho.co.uk/images/who%27%20who%20website%202010.pdf|date=October 2010|publisher=British Bangla Media Group|page=112|isbn= |accessdate=18 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"tulipsiddiq\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tulipsiddiq.com/TulipSiddiq-FortuneGreen1.pdf|title=introducing Tulip Siddiq: your Labour voice in Fortune Green|publisher=Tulip Siddiq|year=2008|accessdate=1 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nHer maternal grandfather is [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]], founding father and the first [[President of Bangladesh]].<ref name=\"independent1\">{{cite news |last=Hensher|first=Philip|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/tulip-siddiq-a-heritage-in-bangadeshi-politics-a-future-in-british-8720884.html|title=Tulip Siddiq: A heritage in Bangadeshi politics, a future in British?|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=19 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> Her mother's elder sister is Prime Minister of Bangladesh [[Sheikh Hasina]].<ref name=\"sylhettimesdigital\"/><ref name=\"aljazeera\">{{cite news |last=Neild|first=Barry|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/01/uk-vote-could-create-cross-border-dynasty-2014113112342206325.html|title=UK vote could create cross-border dynasty|work= |location=Qatar|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=15 January 2014|accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref> \nIn 1975, [[Bangladesh Army]] soldiers stormed Siddiq's mother's home in Bangladesh and [[Assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman|assassinated Siddiq's grandfather, Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]], alongside his three sons<ref name=\"independent2\"/> and 16 other members of his family<ref name=\"hamhigh6\">{{cite news |last=Lamden|first=Tim|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/politics/tulip_siddiq_s_maiden_commons_speech_open_door_immigration_vital_to_hampstead_and_kilburn_1_4115991|title=Tulip Siddiq's maiden Commons speech: 'Open door immigration vital to Hampstead and Kilburn'|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=17 June 2015|accessdate=1 July 2015}}</ref> in a military coup. Siddiq's mother and aunt survived as they were visiting [[Germany]].<ref name=\"independent2\"/>\n\n==Early political career==\nAt the age of 16, Siddiq joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].<ref name=\"standard1\"/> Siddiq's father suffered a stroke, which left him disabled<ref name=\"independent2\"/> and unable to speak for five years.<ref name=\"standard4\"/><ref name=\"independent2\"/> She has cited the [[National Health Service|NHS]] and the care her disabled father received as the reason why she joined.<ref name=\"kilburntimes1\"/> She identified [[Barbara Castle, Baroness Castle of Blackburn|Barbara Castle]] as her political heroine.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\"/> and has described her mother and maternal aunt as \"two very strong feminists\".<ref name=\"independent3\">{{cite news |last=Siddiq|first=Tulip|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tulip-siddiq-the-north-london-labour-candidate-trying-to-improve-the-woeful-diversity-of-westminster-10157378.html|title=Why do we still cling to the belief that most rapes are committed by strangers in dark alleyways?|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=26 November 2015|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe has worked for [[Amnesty International]],<ref name=\"standard4\"/> the [[Greater London Authority]],<ref name=\"labourcouncillor\">{{cite news|url=http://www.labourcouncillor.org.uk/tulip_siddiq|title=Tulip Siddiq \u2013 Camden candidate for 2010 elections|publisher=Labour Councillor|accessdate=18 September 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203011400/http://www.labourcouncillor.org.uk/tulip_siddiq|archivedate=3 December 2011}}</ref> at Philip Gould Associates, the political consultancy firm run by [[New Labour]] strategist [[Philip Gould, Baron Gould of Brookwood|Philip Gould]],<ref name=\"hamhigh3\"/><ref name=\"standard4\"/> [[Save the Children]], and Brunswick, where she worked on corporate social responsibilities initiatives for major British manufacturers, as well as for MPs [[Oona King]], [[Sadiq Khan]] and<ref name=\"bbwhoswho10\"/> [[Harry Cohen]]. Siddiq worked on [[Ed Miliband]]'s campaign to be leader of the Labour Party,<ref name=\"labourcouncillor\"/> and as a special advisor to [[Tessa Jowell]].<ref name=\"standard1\"/> She has campaigned for political parties internationally and, in 2008, campaigned for [[Barack Obama]] in the U.S.<ref name=\"bbwhoswho10\"/>\n\nIn a 2006 by-election, Siddiq stood unsuccessfully for Camden Council.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\"/> In the [[2010 United Kingdom local elections|2010 local government elections]], Siddiq became the first female Bangladeshi councillor for Camden Council,<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite news |last=Wilkinson|first=Michael|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/general-election-2015/11377416/General-Election-2015-the-seats-that-will-decide-who-wins.html|title=9 seats that will decide who wins the General Election|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=30 January 2015|accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref> where she was Cabinet Member for Culture and Communities until [[2014 Camden London Borough Council election|May 2014]].<ref name=\"theguardian1\">{{cite news |last=Siddiq|first=Tulip|url=https://www.theguardian.com/local-government-network/2013/dec/12/library-cuts-volunteers-saved-camdens-libraries|title=How a team of volunteers saved Camden's at risk libraries|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=13 December 2013|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, Siddiq was selected by local party members as the Labour [[prospective parliamentary candidate]] for the [[Hampstead and Kilburn (UK Parliament constituency)|Hampstead and Kilburn constituency]],<ref name=\"kilburntimes1\">{{cite news |last=Beioley|first=Katie|url=http://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/camden_councillor_tulip_siddiq_selected_as_labour_s_prospective_parliamentary_candidate_for_hampstead_and_kilburn_1_2279426|title=Camden councillor Tulip Siddiq selected as Labour's Prospective Parliamentary Candidate for Hampstead and Kilburn|work= |location=Kilburn|publisher=[[Kilburn Times]]|date=15 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"hamhigh2\">{{cite news |last=Beioley|first=Katie|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/tulip_siddiq_selected_as_labour_s_candidate_for_hampstead_and_kilburn_1_2278223|title=Tulip Siddiq selected as Labour's candidate for Hampstead and Kilburn|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=15 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"standard2\">{{cite news |last1=Pettitt|first1=Josh|last2=Watts|first2=Joe|last3=Neicho|first3=Josh |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/labour-selection-contest-for-hampstead-and-kilburn-ends-in-brawl-8708941.html|title=Labour selection contest for Hampstead and Kilburn ends in brawl|location=London|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=15 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"obv\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.obv.org.uk/news-blogs/tulip-siddiq-wining-against-odds|title=Tulip Siddiq: Wining against the odds|work=Operation Black Vote|date=19 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"easterneye\">{{cite news|url=http://www.easterneye.eu/news.html?groupId=15&newsId=2061|title=New Labour candidate Tulip has politics in her blood|work=[[Eastern Eye]]|location=London|date=July 2013|archive-url=https://archive.today/20131201001135/http://www.easterneye.eu/news.html?groupId=15&newsId=2061|archive-date=1 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"indiaweekly\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.indiaweekly.co.uk/news.html?groupId=7&newsId=2061|title=New Labour candidate Tulip has politics in her blood|work= |location=India|publisher=[[India Weekly]]|date= |accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"camdennewjournal3\">{{cite news |last=Osley|first=Richard|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2013/jul/tulip-siddiq-wins-round-one%E2%80%A6-now-real-battle-bid-win-hampstead-and-kilburn-seat-labour|title=Tulip Siddiq wins round one\u2026 now for the real battle in bid to win Hampstead and Kilburn seat for Labour Party|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=18 July 2013|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> despite <!-- Read the source, not in dispute. -->a [[smear campaign]].<ref name=\"hamhigh1\">{{cite news |last=Lamden|first=Tim|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/hampstead_and_kilburn_parliamentary_candidate_tulip_siddiq_hits_back_at_smear_campaign_1_2273210|title=Tulip Siddiq hits back at smear campaign|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=11 July 2013|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> During 2013 and 2014, she campaigned against the proposed high-speed railway expansion [[High Speed 2]],<ref name=\"camdennewjournal5\">{{cite news |last=Foot|first=Tom|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2014/feb/hs2-another-crammed-public-meeting-another-legion-opponents-high-speed-rail-chaos|title=HS2: Another crammed public meeting, another legion of opponents to high speed rail chaos|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=13 February 2014|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> and high pay day lender charges on [[Kilburn High Road]].<ref name=\"kilburntimes1\"/> She also campaigned in support of local services, such as to keep Belsize Fire Station open,<ref name=\"camdennewjournal2\">{{cite news |last=Foot|first=Tom|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2013/jun/meeting-told-how-mayor-boris%E2%80%99s-proposals-axe-fire-stations-will-threaten-safety-high-r|title=Meeting told how Mayor Boris's proposals to axe fire stations will threaten safety of 'high-rise towers'|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=6 June 2013|accessdate=12 January 2015}}</ref> to improve disabled access at [[West Hampstead tube station]]<ref name=\"camdennewjournal6\">{{cite news |last=Hutton|first=Alice|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/West-Hampstead-lift|title=West Hampstead tube station must get lift, campaigners cry|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=24 September 2014|accessdate=12 January 2015}}</ref> and to save the Swiss Cottage post office.<ref name=\"camdennewjournal4\">{{cite news |last=Foot|first=Tom|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2013/sep/plea-save-swiss-cottage-post-office-gets-louder|title=Plea to save Swiss Cottage post office gets louder|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=19 September 2013|accessdate=12 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nIn the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], Siddiq won the Hampstead and Kilburn seat with 23,977 votes, with a turnout of 67.3%.<ref name=\"bdnews246\">{{cite news |last=Pasha|first=Syed Nahas|url=http://www.bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2015/05/08/ive-learned-politics-from-my-aunt-sheikh-hasina-tulip-siddiq|title=New British MP Tulip Siddiq says she learned politics from aunt Sheikh Hasina|work= |location=London|publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=8 May 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"hamhigh4\">{{cite news |last=Beioley|first=Katie|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/home/election-2015/tulip_siddiq_hampstead_and_kilburn_is_my_home_and_i_m_so_proud_to_represent_it_1_4065675|title=Tulip Siddiq: 'Hampstead and Kilburn is my home and I'm so proud to represent it'|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=8 May 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> The seat was previously held by [[Glenda Jackson]].<ref name=\"camdennewjournal7\">{{cite news |last=Osley|first=Richard|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2015/may/full-story-tulip-siddiq-defends-hampstead-and-kilburn-parliamentary-seat-labour|title=Full story: Tulip Siddiq defends Hampstead and Kilburn parliamentary seat for Labour|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=8 May 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> The seat had previously been the second most marginal in the country after Jackson retained the seat by just 42 votes in 2010<ref name=\"thejc1\">{{cite news |last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/135987/election-2015-tulip-siddiq-secures-hampstead-and-kilburn-labour|title=Election 2015: Tulip Siddiq secures Hampstead and Kilburn for Labour|newspaper=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=8 May 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> and was billed in 2015 as the UK's most marginal general election contest.<ref name=\"kilburntimes2\">{{cite news |last=Beioley|first=Katie|url=http://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/home/election-2015/hampstead_and_kilburn_general_election_2015_polling_day_in_england_s_most_marginal_seat_1_4064112|title=Hampstead and Kilburn general election 2015: Polling day in England's most marginal seat|work= |location=Kilburn|publisher=[[Kilburn Times]]|date=7 May 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> In June 2015, Siddiq was appointed a vice-chair of the [[All-Party Parliamentary Group against Antisemitism]].<ref name=\"hamhigh5\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/politics/hampstead_and_kilburn_mp_tulip_siddiq_praised_for_early_role_tackling_anti_semitism_1_4105621|title=Hampstead and Kilburn MP Tulip Siddiq praised for early role tackling anti-Semitism|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=9 June 2015|accessdate=1 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"thejc2\">{{cite news | last1=Streeting|first1=Wes|last2=Siddiq|first2=Tulip|url=https://www.thejc.com/comment/comment/wes-streeting-and-tulip-siddiq-1.436660|title=We've heard your anxieties loud and clear|newspaper=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=24 April 2017|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref> She is also a member of the [[Women and Equalities Committee|Women and Equalities Select Committee]].<ref name=\"parliament\">{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/tulip-siddiq/4518|title=Tulip Siddiq MP|publisher=UK Parliament|date= |accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref> In the same month, she was one of 36 Labour MPs to nominate [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as a candidate in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Labour leadership election]],<ref name=\"newstatesman\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/06/who-nominated-who-2015-labour-leadership-election|title=Who nominated who for the 2015 Labour leadership election?|magazine=[[New Statesman]]|date=15 June 2015|accessdate=8 September 2015}}</ref> although she later supported [[Andy Burnham]].<ref name=\"standard5\">{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/why-labours-rising-star-tulip-siddiq-is-taking-maternity-leave-a3159106.html|title=Labour's rising star Tulip Siddiq on why maternity leave shouldn't be a problem in politics|location=London|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=18 January 2016|accessdate=18 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Siddiq along with [[Keir Starmer]] and [[Catherine West]] wrote a letter to British Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] seeking urgent action to address the [[Refugees of the Syrian Civil War|refugee crisis]] due to the [[Syrian Civil War]].<ref name=\"theguardian3\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/04/britain-best-placed-to-lead-international-response-to-the-refugee-crisis|title=Britain best placed to lead international response to the refugee crisis|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=4 September 2015|accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"bdnews247\">{{cite news |last=Pasha|first=Syed Nahas|url=http://www.bdnews24.com/world/2015/09/05/tulip-siddiq-urges-pm-cameron-to-take-urgent-action-to-address-refugee-crisis-in-europe|title=Tulip Siddiq urges PM Cameron to take urgent action to address refugee crisis in Europe|work= |location=London|publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=5 September 2015|accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"prothom-alo1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.en.prothom-alo.com/international/news/78227/Tulip-seeks-action-to-end-refugee-crisis|title=Tulip seeks action to end refugee crisis|location=Dhaka|newspaper=[[Prothom Alo]]|date=5 September 2015|accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref> In the same month, she was appointed Permanent Private Secretary to the Shadow Minister for Culture, Media and Sport, [[Michael Dugher]].<ref name=\"bdnews248\">{{cite news |last=Pasha|first=Syed Nahas|url=http://www.bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2015/09/26/tulip-siddiq-named-for-labour-shadow-job|title=Tulip Siddiq named for Labour 'shadow' job|work= |location=London|publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=26 September 2015|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"dhakatribune1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2015/sep/27/tulip-made-shadow-state-minister|title=Tulip made shadow state minister|location=Dhaka|newspaper=[[Dhaka Tribune]]|date=27 September 2015|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"newsnextbd\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.newsnextbd.com/tulip-made-shadow-minister-in-britain/|title=Tulip made shadow minister in Britain |work= |location=Bangladesh|publisher=Newsnext Bangladesh|date=27 September 2015|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"thedailystar2\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/tulip-siddiq-shadow-cabinet-labour-party-148966|title=Tulip Siddiq in shadow cabinet of Labour Party|location=Bangladesh|newspaper=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|date=29 September 2015|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref> In November 2015, she campaigned against changes to junior doctor contracts.<ref name=\"camdennewjournal8\">{{cite news |last=Osley|first=Richard|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/tuliphunt|title=New MP Tulip Siddiq challenges Health Secretary Jeremy Hunt to meet frustrated junior doctors at Royal Free|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=5 November 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> In the same month, Siddiq's maiden speech in Parliament was judged one of the top seven from 2015's intake of MPs by the BBC.<ref name=\"hamhigh7\">{{cite news |last=Roberts|first=Rachel|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/politics/hampstead_and_kilburn_mp_tulip_siddiq_s_maiden_speech_judged_in_top_seven_by_bbc_1_4295775|title=Hampstead and Kilburn MP Tulip Siddiq's maiden speech judged in top seven by BBC|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=3 November 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> In October 2016, she was appointed as Shadow Education Minister in the [[Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn|Labour Party's frontbench in Parliament]],<ref name=\"hamhigh9\">{{cite news |last=Banks|first=Emily|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/politics/tulip-siddiq-given-early-years-role-in-corbyn-s-shadow-cabinet-1-4728884|title=Tulip Siddiq given early years role in Corbyn's shadow cabinet|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=9 October 2016|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"thedailystar4\">{{cite news |last=Liton|first=Shakhawat|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/city/tulip-gives-birth-girl-1206841|title=Tulip Siddiq and our MPs|location=Bangladesh|newspaper=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|date=2 February 2016|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref> taking on the childcare and early years education brief and working with [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]] [[Angela Rayner]].<ref name=\"camdennewjournal11\">{{cite news |last=Osley|first=Richard|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/tulip-siddiq-shadow-corbyn|title=Hampstead and Kilburn MP Tulip Siddiq accepts education job in Jeremy Corbyn's team at House of Commons|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=9 October 2016|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Siddiq supported a motion in Parliament for the UK to withdraw support for the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]].<ref name=\"5pillarsuk\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.5pillarsuk.com/2016/11/01/which-muslim-mps-voted-to-stop-arms-sales-to-saudi-arabia/|title=Which Muslim MPs voted to stop arms sales to Saudi Arabia?|work= |location= |publisher=5Pillars|date=1 November 2016|accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref> In January 2017, she resigned from the Labour frontbench over Labour's [[three-line whip]] to vote against triggering [[Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union]]. Siddiq stated that because around 75% of her Hampstead and Kilburn constituency voted to remain in the [[European Union]] as one of the top 10 remain areas, she could not \"reconcile\" herself with Labour's position.<ref name=\"theguardian4\">{{cite news |last=Elgot|first=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jan/26/labour-mp-tulip-siddiq-resigns-from-frontbench-over-article-50-vote |title=Labour MP Tulip Siddiq resigns from frontbench over article 50 vote|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=26 January 2017|accessdate=5 April 2017}}</ref> Siddiq won an endorsement from Camden for Europe, [[Open Britain]] and [[Best for Britain]], due to her decision to vote against Article 50.<ref name=\"camdennewjournal13\">{{cite news |last=Osley|first=Richard|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/article/hampstead-and-kilburn-gina-miller-teams-up-with-tulip-siddiq-as-election-race-gets-tactical|title=UKIP target anti-Brexit Tulip Siddiq by\u2026 not standing a candidate against her|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=18 May 2017|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|general election]], Siddiq retained her seat with an increased majority of 15,560.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000727|title=Hampstead & Kilburn parliamentary constituency - Election 2017|work=[[BBC News]]|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"standard6\">{{cite news |last=De Peyer|first=Robin|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/hampstead-and-kilburn-election-results-who-is-the-mp-for-the-constituency-after-the-general-election-a3547426.html|title=Hampstead and Kilburn election results: Labour's Tulip Siddiq wins north west London constituency|location=London|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"camdennewjournal12\">{{cite news |last=Osley|first=Richard|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/article/neck-and-neck-tulip-siddiq-holds-hampstead-and-kilburn-with-five-figure-majority|title=Neck and neck? Tulip Siddiq holds Hampstead and Kilburn with five-figure majority|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"standard7\">{{cite news |last=Kirk|first=Tristan|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/general-election-2017-may-underestimated-the-british-public-says-tulip-siddiq-a3560716.html|title=Theresa May 'underestimated the British public' says Tulip Siddiq|location=London|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Siddiq called for businesses to \"address imbalance\" in the employment of BAME individuals to improve the diversity of its workforce.<ref name=\"voice-online\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/do-british-businesses-employ-enough-bame-individuals|title=Do British businesses employ enough BAME individuals?|work= |location= |publisher=[[The Voice (British newspaper)|The Voice]]|date=30 August 2017|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref> In September 2017, Siddiq was appointed as Chair of the new Childcare and Early Education All-Party Parliamentary Group (APPG).<ref name=\"nurseryworld\">{{cite news |last=Morton|first=Katy|url=http://www.nurseryworld.co.uk/nursery-world/news/1162159/tulip-siddiq-named-chair-of-early-years-appg|title=Tulip Siddiq named chair of early years APPG|work= |location= |publisher=[[Nursery World]]|date=7 September 2017|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref> In the same month, Siddiq wrote to the [[Home Office]] to ask for children's passports to be amended to contain both their parents' names to avoid confusion at airports and borders. Siddiq had been stopped with her daughter at UK border control whilst returning from a family holiday until her husband joined them, because she did not have the same surname in her passport as her child.<ref name=\"theguardian6\">{{cite news |last=Elgot|first=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/sep/06/mp-stopped-at-border-over-daughters-name-urges-passports-reform|title=MP stopped at border over daughter's name urges passport reform|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=6 September 2017|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"standard8\">{{cite news |last=Grafton-Green|first=Patrick|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/mp-tulip-siddiq-reveals-she-was-stopped-by-border-control-over-her-daughters-name-a3629391.html|title=MP Tulip Siddiq reveals she was stopped by border control over her daughter's name|location=London|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=7 September 2017|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"refinery29\">{{cite news |last=Gill|first=Natalie|url=http://www.refinery29.uk/2017/09/171196/mothers-surnames-childrens-passports-marriage-tulip-siddiq|title=Mothers Surnames Childrens Passports \u2013 Tulip Siddiq MP|work= |location= |publisher=[[Refinery29]]|date=7 September 2017|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref> In November 2017, whilst campaigning for the release of her constituent, the British-Iranian citizen [[Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe]], who is detained in Iran, she was asked by [[Alex Thomson (journalist)|Alex Thomson]] of ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' and [[ITN]] about using her family ties to the Bangladeshi government, led by her aunt, in order to liberate British Bangladeshi barrister Ahmad bin Quasem, who is thought to have been abducted by state security forces in Bangladesh. The programme's editor, [[Ben de Pear]], complained about Siddiq's \"threatening behaviour\" to a pregnant producer, while Siddiq complained to the police about her interlocutors.<ref name=\"telegraph2\">{{cite news |last1=Jamieson|first1=Sophie|last2=Hope|first2=Christopher|last3=Horton|first3=Helena|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/28/labour-mp-makes-threatening-remark-pregnant-journalist/|title=Labour MP Tulip Siddiq makes 'threatening' remark to pregnant journalist |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=29 November 2017|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"theguardian7\">{{cite news |last=Grierson|first=Jamie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/29/channel-4-news-complains-to-labour-over-tulip-siddiqs-threat|title=Tulip Siddiq apologises for remark to pregnant Channel 4 producer|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=29 November 2017|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"independent5\">{{cite news |last=Peck|first=Tom|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-mp-nazanin-zaghari-ratcliff-free-iran-bangladesh-tulip-siddiq-aunt-prime-minister-sheikh-a8081656.html|title=Labour MP leading campaign to free British citizen in Iran avoids requests to help British man in Bangladesh|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=29 November 2017|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref> She later apologised in a statement to the producer,<!-- who strictly speaking works for ITN, rather than Channel 4. --> Daisy Ayliffe, for the offence caused.<ref name=\"theguardian7\" />\n\nIn May 2018, Siddiq supported an [[Equal pay for equal work|equal pay]] campaign aimed at building pressure on employers.<ref name=\"dhakatribune2\">{{cite news |last=Khanna|first=Aditi|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2015/sep/27/tulip-made-shadow-state-minister|title=Tulip Siddiq backs equal pay campaign in UK|location=Dhaka|newspaper=[[Dhaka Tribune]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref> In the same month, Siddiq described the actions of the [[Israel Defense Forces|Israeli military]] during [[2018 Gaza border protests|demonstrations on the Gaza border]] as \"unjustified\" and \"inhumane\". She said: \"I condemn without reservation these violations of international law and human rights by Israel... The protest has been twofold - to highlight the shocking conditions which Palestinians are forced to live in and to demand their [[Palestinian right of return|right to return]] to their homes...\"<ref name=\"thejc5\">{{cite news |last=Harpin|first=Lee|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-mp-tulip-siddiq-explains-backing-hamas-call-for-palestinians-to-return-to-their-homes-in-israel-1.464207|title=Labour MP explains her call for Palestinians to 'return to their homes' in Israel|newspaper=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=16 May 2018|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> In August 2018, Tulip Siddiq joined international calls for her aunt's government to release Bangladeshi photographer [[Shahidul Alam]], who had been jailed after reporting about protests by schoolchildren over road safety problems, and had subsequently stated he was tortured.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/mp-urges-aunt-to-release-bangladesh-photographer-w9tgs0svw|title=MP urges aunt to release Bangladesh photographer Shahidul Alam|last=|first=|date=28 August 2018|work=The Times|access-date=5 September 2018|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news/world/british-mp-tulip-siddiq-seeks-release-of-photographer-shahidul-alam-1625617|title=Tulip calls for release of Shahidul|last=|first=|date=29 August 2018|work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=5 September 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\nSiddiq was a board member of West Euston Partnership and is governor of the Camden and Islington [[NHS Foundation Trust]].<ref name=\"sylhettimesdigital\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://sylhettimesdigital.co.uk/miliband-praises-young-british-bangladeshi-labour-hopefuls/|title=Miliband praises young British Bangladeshi Labour hopefuls|work= |location= |publisher=The Sylhet Times|date=20 January 2010|accessdate=18 September 2011}}</ref> She served as national BAME (Black, Asian and Minority Ethnic) Officer for [[Young Labour (United Kingdom)|Young Labour]] and Women's Officer for [[London Labour Party|London]] Young Labour. She is an executive board member of [[Unite the Union]], a member of the [[Co-operative Party]], a fellow of the [[Royal Society of Arts]] and is also a member of the Commonwealth Journalists Association (UK).<ref name=\"bbwhoswho10\"/> She also oversaw Camden's engagement with the [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London Olympics]], which saw the launch of three legacy schemes to encourage more physical activities, Camden Sports Academy, School and Community Games, and Pro-Active Ambassadors.<ref name=\"camdennewjournal1\">{{cite news |last=Barnett|first=Steve|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/news/2011/jan/2012-sports-scheme-olympic-hopefuls-support-gold-challenge-initiative-swiss-cottage-le|title=2012 sports scheme \u2013 Olympic hopefuls support Gold Challenge initiative at Swiss Cottage Leisure Centre|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=27 January 2011|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nSiddiq served two years as a [[school governor]] at Beckford Primary School and Richard Cobden Primary School<ref name=\"rcobden\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rcobden.camden.sch.uk/governors_lists.html|title=List of Governors|publisher=Richard Cobden Primary School|date= |accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref> and is a current governor at the Working Men's College in Camden.<ref name=\"wmcollege\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wmcollege.ac.uk/pages/working-mens-college-governors.aspx|title=Working Men's College Governors|publisher=Working Men's College|date= |accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> As of January 2014, Siddiq supports a number of organisations in Hampstead and Kilburn, including school governor roles at Emmanuel Primary School<ref name=\"emmanuel\">{{cite web |url= http://www.emmanuel.camden.sch.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Governors-of-Emmanuel-School.pdf|title=Membership of the Governing Body|publisher=Emmanual Church of England Primary School|date= |accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> and Granville Plus Nursery<ref name=\"granvilleplus\">{{cite web |url=http://www.granvilleplus.org.uk/Governors/|title=Governors|publisher=Granville Plus Nursery School|date= |accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> as well as being a trustee of the Camden Arts Centre.<ref name=\"camdenartscentre\">{{cite web |url=http://www.camdenartscentre.org/contact|title=Contact|publisher=Camden Arts Centre|date= |accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> She has also written for ''[[Hampstead and Highgate Express]]''<ref name=\"bbwhoswho10\"/> as a foreign correspondent, primarily covering the [[Elections in the United States|U.S. elections]].\n\n==Recognition==\nIn January 2013, Siddiq was named in the \"[[British Bangladeshi Power & Inspiration 100]]\".<ref name=\"theindependentbd\"/> In December 2014, she was named by ''[[The Guardian]]'' as \"one to watch\" in British politics.<ref name=\"theguardian2\">{{cite news |last=Cadwalladr|first=Carole|url=https://www.theguardian.com/local-government-network/2013/dec/12/library-cuts-volunteers-saved-camdens-libraries|title=Rising stars of 2015: politician Dan Jarvis|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=28 December 2014|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> In April 2015, ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' described her as one of the \"rising stars\" of the Labour Party.<ref name=\"thesundaytimes\">{{cite news |last1=Shipman|first1=Tim|last2=Woolf|first2=Marie|url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/focus/article1542759.ece|title=Get-ahead gang in a hurry|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=12 April 2015|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"bdnews243\">{{cite news |last=Pasha|first=Syed Nahas|url=http://ww.bdnews24.com/world/2015/04/19/tulip-siddiqs-determined-campaign|title=Tulip Siddiq's determined campaign|work= |location=London|publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=19 April 2015|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSiddiq is a [[Muslim]]<ref name=\"aljazeera\"/> but said she is \"more cultural than religious\".<ref name=\"hamhigh3\"/> In 2013,<ref name=\"thedailystar1\">{{cite news |last=Karim|first=Rezaul|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/beta2/news/on-official-trip-for-nieces-wedding/|title=On official trip, for niece's wedding \u2013 PM flies to London today en route to Belarus|location=Bangladesh|newspaper=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|date=4 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> Siddiq married Christian William St John Percy (born 1984),<ref name=\"telegraphindia\">{{cite news |last=Roy|first=Amit|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1130804/jsp/7days/17192386.jsp|title=Tulip gets the ticket|location=India|newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|Telegraph India]]|date=4 August 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> who is a Cambridge-educated<ref name=\"bangladeshchronicle2\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.bangladeshchronicle.net/index.php/2013/07/he-speaks-chinese-and-is-learning-bangla/|title=He speaks Chinese and is learning Bangla|work= |location=Bangladesh|publisher=The Bangladesh Chronicle|date=8 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> company director<ref name=\"tribuneindia\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/world/b-desh-pm-s-niece-on-verge-of-becoming-british-mp/69775.html|title=B'desh PM's niece on verge of becoming British MP|location=India|work=[[The Tribune (India)|The Tribune]]|date=20 April 2015|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref> and strategy consultant with a background in the British civil service.<ref name=\"bangladeshchronicle2\"/> Siddiq lives in a flat on [[Finchley Road]],<ref name=\"hamhigh4\"/> [[West Hampstead]], London with her husband.<ref name=\"kilburntimes1\"/><ref name=\"standard2\"/><ref name=\"bangladeshchronicle1\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.bangladeshchronicle.net/index.php/2013/06/tulip-weds/|title=So what's his full name?|work= |location=Bangladesh|publisher=The Bangladesh Chronicle|date=8 July 2013|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> In April 2016, Siddiq gave birth to a daughter at the [[Royal Free Hospital]] in Hampstead.<ref name=\"hamhigh8\">{{cite news |last=Roberts|first=Rachel|url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/hampstead_and_kilburn_mp_tulip_siddiq_gives_birth_to_her_first_baby_1_4488924|title=Hampstead and Kilburn MP Tulip Siddiq gives birth to her first baby|work= |location=Hampstead and Highgate|publisher=[[Ham & High]]|date=9 April 2016|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"camdennewjournal10\">{{cite news |last=Osley|first=Richard|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/azalea-percy|title=Hampstead and Kilburn MP Tulip Siddiq gives birth to first child|work= |location=Camden|publisher=[[Camden New Journal]]|date=9 April 2016|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"bdnews2410\">{{cite news |last= |first=|url=http://www.bdnews24.com/politics/2016/04/09/tulip-siddiq-gives-birth-to-a-baby-girl|title=Tulip Siddiq gives birth to a baby girl|work= |location= |publisher=[[Bdnews24.com]]|date=9 April 2016|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"prothom-alo2\">{{cite news |url=http://www.en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/101137/Tulip-Siddiq-blessed-with-daughter|title=Tulip Siddiq blessed with daughter|location=Dhaka|newspaper=[[Prothom Alo]]|date=9 April 2016|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"thedailystar3\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/city/tulip-gives-birth-girl-1206841|title=Hasina becomes great-aunt|location=Bangladesh|newspaper=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|date=10 April 2016|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref> Tulip Siddiq's husband Christian William St John Percy is a [[Christians|Christian]] by [[religion]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.elle.com/uk/life-and-culture/culture/a20741768/this-is-modern-love/ |title = Modern Love: Meet the Couples Redefining What It Looks Like in 2018|date = 18 May 2018}}</ref> Siddiq herself told in an interview that \"I\u2019m Muslim and Chris is Christian, but we\u2019ve just maintained our own culture and religion by taking an interest in each other\u2019s. We\u2019re teaching our daughter both and then she\u2019ll choose when she\u2019s older. She\u2019ll do Muslim and Bangladeshi cultural things with me, but she also knows what church is like.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.elle.com/uk/life-and-culture/culture/a20741768/this-is-modern-love/ |title = Modern Love: Meet the Couples Redefining What It Looks Like in 2018|date = 18 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe gave birth to a son in January 2019.<ref name=\"DelayedBirth\">{{cite web |title=MP who delayed birth of son accuses Tories over proxy vote delay |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jan/21/mp-who-delayed-birth-of-son-accuses-tories-over-proxy-vote-delay |website=The Guardian |accessdate=21 January 2019 |date=21 January 2019}}</ref> Two days before the birth she attended the Commons in a wheelchair, for a critical [[Brexit]]-related [[Meaningful vote|vote]].<ref name=\"DelayedBirth\" /> On 29 January, following a constitutional change, she became the first ever MP to vote by proxy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-47061992/labour-mp-tulip-siddiq-allowed-proxy-votes-for-brexit|work=BBC News|title=Labour MP Tulip Siddiq allowed proxy votes for Brexit|date=30 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nSiddiq's daughter attends a Jewish nursery. Since becoming an MP, Siddiq has spoken at [[Limmud]] and attends synagogue events.<ref name=\"thejc4\">{{cite news |last=Harpin|first=Lee|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/tulip-siddiq-i-have-been-active-in-speaking-out-against-antisemitism-1.438440|title=Tulip Siddiq: 'I have been active in speaking out against antisemitism'|newspaper=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=12 May 2017|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> In April 2019, Siddiq announced that a relative died in the [[2019 Sri Lanka Easter bombings]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Victims of Sri Lanka terror attacks revealed: who were they? |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/victims-of-sri-lanka-terror-attacks-revealed-who-were-they |work=SBS News |date=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[British Bangladeshi]]\n*[[List of British Bangladeshis]]\n*[[List of ethnic minority politicians in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n*{{Official website|http://www.tulipsiddiq.com/}}\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=tulip-siddiq/4518 |publicwhip=Tulip_Siddiq |theywork=tulip_siddiq}}\n*[http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/tulip-siddiq/ Tulip Siddiq] on ''[[Huffington Post]]''\n*[http://democracy.camden.gov.uk/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=217 Tulip Siddiq] on Camden Council\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* {{cite news | last = Siddiq | first = Tulip | title = How to engage ethnic minorities with democracy | url =  http://compassonline.org.uk/news/item.asp?n=4522 | work = Compass | date = 18 May 2009}}\n* {{cite news | last = Siddiq | first = Tulip | title = The pessimism of Baroness Warsi | url = http://labourlist.org/tulip-siddiq-the-pessimism-of-baroness-warsi | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101219204142/http://labourlist.org/tulip-siddiq-the-pessimism-of-baroness-warsi | url-status = dead | archive-date = 19 December 2010 | work = Labour List | date = 3 October 2010}}\n* {{cite news | last = Siddiq | first = Tulip | title = How I'm trying to stop library cuts in Camden | url = http://liberalconspiracy.org/2011/03/08/how-ive-tried-to-stop-library-cuts-in-camden/ | work = Liberal Conspiracy | date = 8 March 2011}}\n{{col-2}}\n* {{cite news | last = Siddiq | first = Tulip | title = How a team of volunteers saved Camden's at risk libraries | url = https://www.theguardian.com/local-government-network/2013/dec/12/library-cuts-volunteers-saved-camdens-libraries | work = [[The Guardian]] | date = 13 December 2013}}\n* {{cite news | last = Lamden | first = Tim | title = Hampstead and Kilburn general election 2015: Labour candidate Tulip Siddiq's final word | url = http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/home/election-2015/hampstead_and_kilburn_general_election_2015_labour_candidate_tulip_siddiq_s_final_word_1_4063113 | work = [[Ham & High]] | date = 7 May 2015}}\n* {{cite news | last = Bennett | first = Owen | title =  Tulip Siddiq On Glenda Jackson, Why Obama Could Only Fall From The Pedestal, And Why Work Never Stops Even At Zumba Class | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/10/19/tulip-siddiq-glenda-jackson-springsteen_n_8330872.html | work = [[The Huffington Post]] | date = 20 October 2015}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Glenda Jackson]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n |title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Hampstead and Kilburn (UK Parliament constituency)|Hampstead and Kilburn]]\n |years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{London Labour Party MPs}}\n{{Sheikh Mujibur Rahman}}\n{{Sheikh Hasina}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Siddiq, Tulip}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English Muslims]]\n[[Category:English people of Bangladeshi descent]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of 